__label__NewZealand stand still. the trees ahead and bushes beside you
are not lost. wherever you are is called here,
and you must treat it as a powerful stranger,
must ask permission to know it and be known.
the forest breathes. listen. it answers.
if what a tree or a bush does is lost on you,
you are surely lost. stand still. the forest knows
where you are. you must let it find you.

__label__Hawaii #capitalonepartner iâ€™m very excited to be partnering with @capitalone this year on a series of posts - how to spend, save and invest more wisely. of course all of my tips will be travel-based! 
my first post is now live: the ultimate pre-travel checklist. itâ€™s at capital.one/2t420f2 and linked at my profile. i thought through everything that i do before every trip â€“ some money-based, like knowing the foreign exchange rate and having a credit card that doesnâ€™t charge foreign transaction fees, but also things like checking passport expiration dates, looking into insurance and vaccinations, memorizing a few words in the local language, and getting the house ready. and i created a downloadable checklist to make it easy for you to check things off before your next trip. that way you can enjoy your beach vacation instead of stressing! this was earlier this year in hawaii. 
iâ€™d love feedback. is there anything iâ€™m missing? how do you keep track of everything you need to do before you leave?

__label__Canada a dream come true- watching the sun rise over floe lake high in the canadian rockies. i do all my work outside, the seasons pace it, and i work with @canonusa to document the shift between them. nothing makes an alpine photograph like a massive peak reflected on a lake, and this goes back hundreds of years in paintings. in photography itâ€™s a little different because it needs to happen for you capture it.. to make sure the odds are on my side, i check the weather forecast and look for low winds. i wake up way before sunrise, usually the rise of the sun brings thermal winds. and lastly, i pick a low vantage point over the water to maximize the reflection of the landscape on it.. nothing scientific, just prep and a healthy dose of patience. shot on #eos80d with 10-18mm stm lens.

__label__ChiangMai,Thailand while your sitting there telling yourself you can't do something, there's someone else saying you can.
.
.
there's also someone else out there telling themselves they can do something and having the life you want. self doubt is a hard monkey to shake. it'll cling onto you and not let go. it'll engulf you if you let it. .
.
what helps me is small, baby steps. small goals, that once completed, make me feel better. completing these small goals gives me the confidence to make the goals bigger. and before i know it, i've crushed those goals too. .
.
look, nobody can tell you "don't doubt yourself!" and it really stick. you have to realize it for yourself. you can read all the motivational quotes in the world, but if you don't believe it in you, life will never change. .
.
i'll just say this, if this guy can accomplish his dreams, literally anyone can. boy oh boy, if y'all knew the old me.....if i can come out of that alive and keep fighting, you can too. trust me there. .
.
so keep fighting. there's alot to fight for.

__label__Florence,Italy the other day, i posted about indecision. i struggle with it quite often, but as of late, iâ€™ve understood that when we donâ€™t decide, we donâ€™t move forward. it is only when we make decisions, and take actions towards them, that our life can transform for the better. for example:
â €â €â € â €
i decided i would change my life and live it my way, and i did.
â €â €â € â €
i decided that i could circumnavigate the world, and that iâ€™d do so successfully, and thatâ€™s exactly what happened.
â €â €â € â €
i decided that humanity was good, and it has treated me kindly.
â €â €â € â €
none of this happened, nor could have happened, until i decided it was going to. and once i didâ€¦ it was like i flipped a magic switch. i started getting what i wanted from life, and it flowed to me in abundance.
â €â €â € â €
stop sitting on the fence. whatever youâ€™re thinking about, whatever you want with your lifeâ€¦ either commit to doing it, or donâ€™t.
â €â €â € â €
if you make a mistake, you can always adjust course. but if you do nothing, youâ€™ll just be in limbo, constantly oscillating from one possibility to the next and wondering â€œwhat if.â€
â €â €â € â €
decide what you want, and go for it. why live life in-between?

__label__LagunaBeach,California they say you are an average of the five people you spend the most time with. what do you think about that? whether itâ€™s friends, family, co-workers, or whoever else you choose to spend your days with, the people around you mold who you are. itâ€™s important to be open to change too. iâ€™ve learned as you go through stages of your life, those five people may change, but true friendships always endure. i think one of the most important things you can do is always challenge yourself. when i was training to play professional tennis i always tried to practice with people better than me. it wasnâ€™t easy and i often got pushed around the court, but i learned so much and got better quick. same parallels in photography/video. learn from others who inspire you, but take aspects of things you love and create your own style. the same goes both ways. make sure youâ€™re teaching and inspiring others just as much. thereâ€™s so much to learn as you navigate through your life, but helping others is often just as rewarding as self-improvement.

__label__HoChiMinhCity,Vietnam our final stop on our @busaboutasia tour - ho chi minh city/saigon!!! we've been here for a couple days and have done and seen so much already. i have so many things i want to share about this city, especially given its unfortunate history with america, and some things i've noticed in regards to that.

but before i address that, here are some fun facts to help contextualize the monstrosity of this city and the uniqueness it encompasses.

1. it's the largest city in vietnam and was formerly the capital of the french colony of cochinchina. because of this, you see so much western influence, and the beauty and juxtaposition of asian and french architecture is absolutely stunning. this is also the only city in vietnam with a mcdonald's! #murica

2. the languages spoken include vietnamese, cantonese, teochew, hokkien, hainanese and hakka dialects of chinese, mandarin, and english.

3. over 3 million people visit ho chi minh city every year, which accounts for nearly 70% of all tourism in vietnam.

4. hcmc's population is over 9 million and expected to rise to almost 14 million in 10 years due to it being the economic center where people from the north migrate for work.

5. yellow traffic lights literally mean to speed up, not slow down. but there are essentially no rules on the road. you could legitimately set out a picnic in the middle of the busiest roundabout in this city and you will go untouched.

these are the craziest yet most efficient drivers i have ever seen. toddlers, refrigerators, bags of rice, or live chicken hanging by the feet are all normal things you might see on the backseat of a motorbike. can't wait to share footage!

this city, simply put, is unreal and excuse my inability to form comprehensive sentences to adequately summarize my thoughts. still allowing myself to process this magnetic environment. more soon. what a city. what a country. â¤

__label__Lofoten taking a leap into the unknown is scary. we can plan for it, believe in ourselves, predict various potential outcomes, and yet... we still have no guarantees that itâ€™ll work out.
â €â €â € â €
there is an element of uncertainty in everything that we do. every day, we are taking risks: we can walk outside and get hit by a car, awkwardly run into an ex, be unexpectedly fired, the list goes on.
â €â €â € â €
so what gives - why is going after what you truly want any scarier than staying where you already are?
â €â €â € â €
i get it. the closer you get to what you want, the more unbearable the uncertainty feels. and guess what - itâ€™s ok to feel that way, and then move past that feeling.
â €â €â € â €
you are already taking a risk by being a breathing, living organism operating in your current conditions, so why not make decisions that could actually change your life for the better?
â €â €â € â €
kiss that person, ask for that raise, start that business. try it despite the uncertainty and give it your best. maybe even fail at it. then get up, and try again.
â €â €â € â €
the possibilities for success are infinite, and our time is finite.
â €â €â € â €
you will never know how your leap of faith works out. but you will know that you gave this life your best, and that in itself makes any risk worth it.

__label__Prague,CzechRepublic before visiting #prague for the first time this week, i googled #travelblogger reviews and i was a little taken aback by the number of reviews from black #bloggers who considered #czechs in the city to be racist because of their cold stares, etc. but being here (and coming from usa tbh) i've found that to be personally untrue (especially compared to usa). how have we come to the point that we construe a long glance from another human a negative action? a stare really could mean 'hello', 'fuck you', or 'let's fuck'. imo eye contact is really the most primative form of #communication. an expression of curiosity from which you can determine a fight or flight response, etc. #blackisbeautiful and people naturally stare at beautiful things. so why not reply with a #smile instead of suspicion? it's worked for me so far.

__label__Cappadocia/Kapadokya i really tried to narrow down these pictures but it was impossible. cappadocia, turkey in the winter is one of the most magical places iâ€™ve visited. it has been on my bucket list for years and iâ€™m so glad i went. 
cappadocia is located pretty much in the middle of the country. itâ€™s a quick 80min flight from istanbul making it an easy weekend trip. the region is geographically beautiful and probably most well known for its phallic looking rock formations otherwise known as â€œfairy chimneys.â€ i visited the area back in 2012 in the spring and at that time spent a few days visiting the gÃ¶reme open air museum and the rock churches with beautifully preserved mosaics that the region is known for. we hiked a bit and visited the underground cities and went hot air ballooning. it was amazing. 
then a couple years later i saw pictures on a travel blog of hot air ballooning in the winter and i wanted to go back ever since. i wanted to see the region blanketed in snow. cappadocia is the hot air ballooning capital of the world. but hot air ballooning is unpredictable. itâ€™s so weather dependant. if itâ€™s windy you canâ€™t fly and so on the morning of my scheduled flight i was tempted to reschedule seeing as it was -21c but i knew iâ€™d risk not getting to go at all. so i bundled up and took a few hundred pictures. every view was amazing. the rising sun coming up against the landscape with balloons doting the horizon was mesmerizing. 
the rest of the two days i spend there were mostly just to relax. i sipped wine by the fire. read. did some writing and lazily soaked in an amazing deep soaking tub. it was perfect!

__label__Bali,Indonesia networking up: when's the last time you reached out to someone who was 10x more powerful than you?

how intimidating was it and did your email have ğŸ’© smears from the virtual pants-sh*tting?

i recently had to look at my network and reach out to the 10 most powerful people in it and ask for a favor, because with these new goals i have, i'm not foolish to think i will ever get there on my own.

it'll require others to vouch for me, connect with me, and constructively criticize me and i can't tell you how humbled i've been by it.

i'm not a name-dropper, but i'm blessed to know a few millionaires on a first-name basis.

in comparison, lil' ol me has nothing of equal weight to offer, but here's why they respond to my requests 99% of the time.

i treat them like a human, not a dollar amount.

i respect their time.

i don't assume a yes.

i've interacted or engaged with them dozens of times without ever asking for anything.

i've supported their work in the past.

i share my goals and my mission.

i let them know how grateful i am for their time/consideration, even if they can't help.

one thing that's the most disheartening about people who email me asking for favors, is that they do none of the above.

they treat me like a step on a ladder/a way of getting ahead.

they demand a response immediately.

they assume a yes.

they've never engaged with a single social media post.

they've never supported my work.

they don't share their goals.

they rarely answer back after i've helped them out.

e-mail etiquette is a thing y'all. study it and implement those habits into your everyday virtual interactions.

the same goes for dms and fb messenger.

there are ways to network with powerful people, you just need to learn to come correct.

feel free to drop any other tips below!

__label__PhiPhiIslands i celebrate myself, but the celebration remains in my head. 
i am the only one who knows about it; for it remains unsaid.

if i pranced around saying, "i love me", i would lose all respect, that is a guarantee. 
to celebrate such a silly thing as myself, it would be rude to the nature and her wealth.

we should not celebrate the ever-changing personalities, but clap our hands in appreciation of the ever lasting amenities.

though, if i were to celebrate such a silly thing, i would compare myself to that of a songbird's wing.

__label__Lofoten one of the biggest issues i've had to overcome as a photographer that travels the globe is to learn awareness of the issues facing the places i love & have dedicated my life to documenting. i cringe to think of the times in my life where i've photographed something purely for its beauty while failing to mention that it's under threat & in need of protection. which is why my work documenting iceland's rivers have been more than just an artistic endeavor for likes. .
the latest issue that has been brought to my attention from the many passionate locals & incredible messages from people like you - is the potential for oil drilling in norway's lofoten islands as well as other neighboring locations. 
i cannot express the beauty & importance of this wild place & as always i hope you do your own research & form an educated decision. if you have been inspired by this landscape then i urge you to speak out as the window to be heard is now.
.

negotiations to open the area for drilling start after sept 11 & the fate of this landscape falls upon the 
norwegian prime minister candidates @jonasgahrs & @erna_solberg . feel free to tag them in a comment expressing your position or express your feelings to them directly. for more info check out www.lovese.no

__label__Miami,Florida as the largest organ of the body, the skinâ€™s primary function is to detox and filter. skin is a reflection of oneâ€™s internal health.

it might sound weird, but i often prefer to photograph myself. i still get camera shy if someone is shooting me. and, i am a photographer at heart. so itâ€™s a fun challenge to be creative with how i shoot. for photos like this, i set up my tripod and put my camera on an interval timer setting to take a photo every second for 50 photos and then pick my favorite from the batch. i am able to get my composition and lighting right before pressing the shutter and jumping into frame. i probably look like a crazy tourist but it feels more natural for me and i end up looking way more comfortable in photos.

a few quick tips for self-shooting:
1. donâ€™t be embarrassed. theyâ€™re your memories and you canâ€™t expect someone to always be there to capture them for you.
2. read up on the rule of 3rds. itâ€™s not the end-all-be-all of composition, but itâ€™s a good guideline to work from (youâ€™ll understand why i was so satisfied with my lines in this shotâ€” thanks ğŸ¦!)
3. donâ€™t skip the edit. i shoot in raw (it gives more flexibility with your post-processing) and use my lightroom @tbapresets for desktop and mobile!

__label__RiodeJaneiro,RiodeJaneiro are you coming with us to down to brazil for rio carnival 2019!? join us!! when i was building this trip to rio i scored a behind the scenes pass at the cidade do samba, the warehouse where some of the top schools prepare their floats, costumes and choreography for the  biggest party on earth!

along with the tour i got to learn the original history of samba and carnival. not the white-washed version we all get because we are disconnected from our international brothers and sisters. 
did you know that carnival, the half a 600 million dollar yearly parade in rio de janeiro, is largely existing because of one black slave woman that wasnâ€™t afraid to break the rules?

the legend states that tia ciata migrated from bahia, brazil down to rio with many other freed slaves in 1875. being that there were little to no places for blacks to congregate publicly, ciata began hosting parties in her house where her community could eat, play music, dance, and fellowship. 
these parties held in the favelas of rio are where the original rhythms of samba were developed. to make this story even more black, these illegal parties were always getting shut down by the.cops for being too lit and too black. 
aside from the perfect host, ciata was also known as a great chef and to have great healing powers as a local leader of the condoblÃ© (dance in honor of the gods) religion. she sold baked treats on the streets of rio and became a mini celebrity for her food, religious ceremonies, and parties at her house. 
the legend continues that one day the late brazilian  president venceslau brÃ¡s called upon her to heal his leg and in return he appointed her husband to the chief of police. 
he decided to continue to keep her parties publicly illegal, however he allotted them to use  a phone in their home that would warn them of police nearby. 
as ciata continued to build the samba scene, it attracted many famous insiders and journalists. â€œpelo telefoneâ€ by ernesto dos santos became the first ever recorded samba song. it was produced in ciataâ€™s house in little africa, a small neighborhood in central rio. .

__label__LosAngeles,California [7/12] itâ€™s nearly impossible to get your first 5,000 subscribers. we remember saying once we reach 8,000 followers, weâ€™ll be happy. there was no real reason; it just sounded like a big number.
ã€°
our days were spent trying not to fall asleep in college lectures (until damon dropped out - jo stuck it out for the last two years, since she had free room & board in manhattan). our nights were spent at grind coworking on 23rd and park, where we would meet after our day-jobs. jo strategically got a front desk job so we could use the space after-hours to edit our videos. damon taught french classes at fluent city in brooklyn, so we could have access to free language classes.
ã€°
our youtube paychecks for the first two years were minimal - literally $1 a day. we did everything from walking a cute-ass dog named gypsy for a fashion designer in chelsea. we delivered groceries with instacart because the app was so beta that nobody placed any orders, which meant we could get paid while editing our videos. there was also a three-day stint at johnny rockets for damon, and an instance where jo walked out on her boss at serafina in the meatpacking district.
ã€°
the real money was in new york city catering, where weâ€™d get emotional when the bride and groom would play their engagement video, as if we were invited to the wedding. weâ€™d eat their cake and clap at the father-daughter dance. weâ€™d offer tuna tartar and sometimes accidentally spill starter salads on people. the highlight was $22/hour, plus a hefty tip from manhattanâ€™s upper crust.
ã€°
and during all these jobs, weâ€™d find time to scrap money together, buy cheap bus tickets to random cities like baltimore, film, edit, and hope for the best after clicking publish. we were disappointing everyone: our bosses, our friends, our lovers, our sleep-deprived eyeballs, but we knew it's what we had to do.
ã€°
our channel wasnâ€™t made overnight.

__label__Bali one of our flaws is that we only value things that feel scarce. daily routines can often lose meaning and value when they feel limitless. sometimes even a beautiful sunset on the way home from work can feel unimportant because â€œthere will always be anotherâ€. a few years ago i began reminding myself every single time i watched the sunset that it could literally be the last time i ever witness it. 
i have never had a greater appreciation for the way the colours change and the sunlight bounces. i try to apply this same thinking to everything that i do and it has always brought a greater appreciation for the moments and things around me. 
even if itâ€™s from the drivers seat of your car on the way home from work, watch your next sunset like it could be your last and i can guarantee you, you will have a new found appreciation for the colours in the sky ğŸŒ…

__label__Honolulu,Hawaii throughout my travels around the world, i am consistently reminded of what it really means to go with the flow. theoretically, flowing should be an easy and smooth process - if you let it. but to most of us, flowing doesnâ€™t come naturally; we have to learn to find inner equilibrium within circumstances that are consistently shifting beyond our control.
.
paddle yoga strangely taught me a lesson on what it means to go with the flow. when the wind blows you a certain direction, donâ€™t fight it - focus on feeling its breeze. when the ground shifts beneath your feet, remember to find your balance. when your surroundings feel strange and unfamiliar, ease yourself into them until they become comfortable. and never forget to occasionally dip your fingers into the water and feel the vast ocean that carries you.
.
challenge yourself. let the flow take you to where you need to be. you may fall off your paddle sometimes, but the good news is, you can always get back up.
.

__label__HongKong photography / instagram tips - always have a clear subject.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
if you want to get the attention of the viewer, the photo canâ€™t be too messy. you only have 1 second before the viewer has judged your photo in their head. after that, you have either caught their attention or lost it.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
if you have a clear subject, itâ€™s easy to look at the photo and by having a main subject in clear focus, you will get the viewerâ€™s attention.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
take this photo for example, the ding ding tram is my main subject, but there are lots of other interesting stuff in the photo as well. however, the other things donâ€™t steal the attention at first glance.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
for me, the local lady and skyscrapers are equally interesting, but you will most likely take a look at these after youâ€™ve seen the main subject - the ding ding tram.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
in photography, and a lot of things in life, less is often more. i often see people wanting to photograph and get everything in the frame, but that can easily make the photo messy.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i will keep sharing photography and instagram tips in every second photo i post ğŸ™‚

__label__Amsterdam,Netherlands i spent 5 blissful 'do nothing' days in amsterdam. long, purposeless walks along the canals of the city. people-watching. browsing quirky stores. reading murakami on a park bench for hours. leaching on to free social wifi by liking a facebook page to check emails. .
.
i loved the feeling of anonymity. no camera, no photos (except some food photos with my iphone ğŸ˜). no agenda. no meetings. no one to catch up with. no commitments. just me and my thoughts. my solitude even in the crowded cobbled streets, even in empty alleyways. .
.
i loved slow, delicious meals at hip vegan cafes... including @roots_amsterdam @laviniagoodfood @dophertamsterdam and @vegabondfood ğŸ” this meal at dophert, with a burger patty made of chickpeas and topped with chipotle mayo, and sweet potato fries with lemon mayo... just yum! .
.
and well, the seriously incredible feeling of walking into a coffeeshop and being asked, "what kind of high are you in the mood for?" the epitome of freedom, if you ask me ğŸ‰ .
.
so yes, 5 blissful days that went by in a blur. and yesterday, i arrived in... wait for it... scotland! âœˆï¸
.
.
got any memories of aimless city wanderings to share?

__label__Kauai all photography, to a certain extent, is a lie. a friend said that to me the other day during a conversation about photoshop and my first impulse was to disagree. but in there somewhere was a seed of truth i mulled over today as i edited. photography is the photographer's imposition and framing of reality. it's the color corrected stopping of time. 
it's confusing and beautiful. manipulative and transportive. is it more important for an image to tell the truth or the truth as i experienced it? this image, for example, you would never know photographer @mikecoots and i were getting absolutely hammered by wind and current. that this was the one area with semi clear water. the lens was finicky and the focus on me is a bit soft. normally that would drive me insane, but it felt right for this one. for the reality i wanted to tell. it was a fun albeit imperfect adventure. does it lose its magic when i tell the truth? does anyone even read a caption this long? ğŸ˜‚sorry, these are the things i think about when i sit at the computer for hours :) #onedayillwriteashortcaption

__label__GrandCanyonNationalPark i remember 10 year ago when i just moved to the states, one of my biggest desires was to be fluent in english. it was so important to me that i even wrote it on piece of paper among other important things that i wanted to accomplish.

when you come to a foreign land everything shifts, you feel like you are almost a new born in a body of an adult, you can move around and do things physically, but you cannot communicate well with others. all you can do is smile and pretend like you understand something and sometimes it can be very awkward when people ask you a question and you answer â€œyesâ€ , where you supposed to say â€œnoâ€, because you didnâ€™t understand the question. at that moment the look on their face is priceless.

__label__Bali,Indonesia who else here lives a life teetering between two extremes?

is it the aries in me? my extroverted introversion? my quarter-life crisis talking?

i'm convinced there's a good chunk of us who go through life trying so hard to listen to the "right" voice when there's 10 others that try to take center stage.

in a world that's very black and white to everyone else, how do you walk the fine line of gray?

we are such passionate souls that we know no middle ground in anything.

we either love something with all our hearts, or reject it with every fiber of our souls.

we either want to be jiggin' in the middle of the dance floor, or completely isolated in the middle of nowhere.

we either want to make close connections to break down our walls, or keep everyone at a 10-foot distance.

why tho?

i've been opening up about these revelations to a handful of friends and it's so empowering to know i'm not alone.

as we blink our eyes and end up in december, it's crazy to think about all the goals we set for ourselves just 11 months back, and how much we've hit or missed the mark since then.

2018 will come with its fair share of life lessons, serendipitous encounters, and dream-chasing, and i hope like hell, i'm ready for it all.

speaking of the new year, if i invited like 4 of you to celebrate new year's eve with me somewhere in central or south america, where should we go? ğŸ¤” #seriousquestion

__label__Norway meet my friend, johann. ğŸ¦Œ johann is a reindeer living in norway's arctic tundra. also, he definitely isn't named johann, i just have a habit of naming every animal i meet and he gave off sort of a "johann-esque" kind of vibe.
.
i'd love to tell you all about the magical time that i had hanging out with johann, feeding him pellets and brushing his soft downy reindeer fur and laughing together about how my hair was frozen because it was -30 degrees outside. but that's not what happened.
.
you see, johann is not yet domesticated, and as a result is very shy around people. a few days before i met him, was living a happy reindeer life in the wild, not realizing that his very existence was made possible by indigenous sÃ¡mi reindeer herders who spend countless hours moving his herd from place to place so that they stay safe from predators and well fed.
.
so johann is still adapting to life as a domestic reindeer. his herders will spend a week or so getting to know him, walking him on a leash, and feeding him pellets while he learns that they mean him no harm. and so because johann wasn't comfortable around me, i refrained from touching him, as pettable and adorable as he looked with his little face and his little horns and those big eyes. instead, i left him some pellets and took a zillion photos of him from a reasonable distance.
.
the sami people have been living in the arctic of modern-day norway, finland, sweden and russia for thousands of years, practicing reindeer husbandry and herding. today, only about 2,800 sami reindeer herders remain, working together to keep their traditions (and their herds) alive. on my trip to norway, i was lucky enough to spend 3 days in the tundra getting to know a family of sÃ¡mi reindeer herders and learning about the choices they make every day to preserve their heritage and culture. today (feb 6) is sami national day, a holiday celebrated by all sami people across their various country borders. happy sami national day!
.
did you know that there are still indigenous people living in the arctic tundra? have you ever met a reindeer? drop your comments and questions below!
.

__label__SanFrancisco,California spent the day in san francisco with @a.study.in.charlotte, another friend i made on instagram. it's crazy how many people i've met through my social network since i set off on my couch-surfing social experiment 7 months ago. everywhere i visit, there is a new person to meet: and more likely than not, i end up really liking them and wanting to stay friends moving forward.
.
i suppose that's how one can make friends all over the world - by putting yourself out there, being vulnerable, and open-minded to new and often unexpected encounters. believe that people will be kind and good, and i can personally vouch that they usually are!

__label__Bali,Indonesia â€œwhen you have more than you need, build a longer table, not a higher fence.â€ your platform is in vain if you amass riches and do nothing to give back.

because of my recent @forbes article (almost 20,000 hits, wow!) and @dearalyne video (620,000 views ğŸ˜­), itâ€™s been inspiring to see how many people of color have hit me up, as thereâ€™s not nearly enough representation of us in the travel media space.

so iâ€™ve been sending tips, pointers, and advice all weekend.

but! if information alone made us rich, weâ€™d all be billionaires.

itâ€™s information, application, and dedication that are the three components to success, so i hope these 3 quick tips will give further inspiration and context.

1. change your circle.

weâ€™ve all heard the quote by jim rohn, â€œyouâ€™re the average of the 5 people you spend the most time with.â€ i didnâ€™t truly understand the power of that until i made it a goal this year to aim to be the dumbest person in the room.

that sounds foolish, but think about it â€” how are you growing if youâ€™re always the one giving information?

i had to start connecting with people who not only made more money than me, but had more experience in more areas.

you donâ€™t have to cut everyone out of your life, just be a bit more selective with who youâ€™re giving your best energy to.

2. start journaling.

i started journaling because i was constantly throwing myself into foreign territory â€” whether the food, the currency, or the culture, everything about my life was a never-ending cycle of adaptation.

i needed some way to center myself and meditation and journaling was the best answer.

3. take money out of the equation.

this sounds counterintuitive, but i need people to understand that if youâ€™re in a profession solely for the money and perks, then youâ€™ll never truly be happy or satisfied.

how i know blogging is for me? because iâ€™d still be doing it if i never made a single dollar from it.

i started my first blog when i was 11, and even though my hard-hitting content was about cute boys at my school ğŸ˜… i developed a voice and sense of liberation from feeling like there was a corner of the internet i could call my own.

__label__BuenosAires,Argentina yo quiero vivir en buenos aires. 
it is cold as balls here so #traveltuesday to beautiful buenos aires, argentina. it was sunny and warm there, the beginning of spring time, when i visited. quite the opposite of the current -30 degrees here in calgary. and although it has been somewhat delayed in happening, my trip to south america is what has motivated me to finally start learning spanish. learning a new language is challenging and can become quite demotivating with its challenges, but i am ready to work hard so i can enjoy south america even more in the future. i only saw a few big cities, so next time i want to go deeper to the places where i won't have english-speaking friends to help me.

and also, argentina was my dream destination and i only ended up going because my shitty ex bailed on coming with me to colombia so i changed ny plans.

__label__Maldives imagine if you will. the sound of heavy rain puts you into a deep slumber. the weather forecast says the next day will be rainy too, so you plan to stay in and work and gaze at the rain. but in the morning, when you open one eye, bright sunlight pours in. when you step out, the air smells of rain, the beach has been washed clean, the ocean is shades of blue again, the gentle waves are caressing the sand.
.
.
so you get into your swimming gear (the sun is really strong, so that means covering up as much as possible), put on some fins, wear a snorkeling mask and wander off into the magical underwater world just off your island. you see eels, schools of big fish, scores of colourful little fish and living corals, and feel like the dimension of time doesn't apply to you anymore.
.
.
that timeless feeling, as i snorkel in the house reef off  @madi_finolhu_guesthouse ğŸ
.
.
shot on @goproin ; edited with @plotagraphpro .
.

__label__Mumbai,Maharashtra a big thank you to everyone who came for the @natgeotravellerindia meetup yesterday! it was such a fun evening, talking about responsible and slow travel, hearing your stories, answering your curious questions (from hitchhiking to how to make your blog stand out), and putting a face to handles i've been tweeting / instagram chatting with for years ğŸ˜‡
.
.

.
.

__label__BrooklynBridge construction on the brooklyn bridge began in 1870 and it officially opened to the public in may of 1883. it was originally called the 'new york and brooklyn bridge' and wasn't officially given the name "brooklyn bridge" until 1915. the bridge was designated a national historic landmark in 1964. i've always loved the neo-gothic architectural style of the structure and the pointed arches that are above the passageways through the two supporting stone towers. but most importantly, because its primary engineer washington roebling -- (who took over from his father who died as a result of an accident during construction) -- designed the bridge to technically be six times stronger than it needed to be at the time, the brooklyn bridge sill stands, while most of the other bridges from that time period have long since fallen down or are simply too unsafe to use!

__label__ChiangMai,Thailand it baffles me that there are some people who go on these amazing trips and donâ€™t have oneÂ picture of themselves from the trip! okay, taking pictures of yourself is awkward, i getÂ it.

your mood, your expression, and yourÂ body all change daily, and you get a chance to see how all of that looked while on a trip, to laugh or gawk at later. ğŸ˜

so embrace the moment!Â not only will it be the best souvenir from your trip, but it humanizes the experience for someone else.

all of a sudden, someone scrolling on their feed goes from - "oh, cool, a travel photo." to - "wait, look, my friend, in a travel photo! that could be me!" you never know who you're inspiring!

__label__Rome,Italy happy new year from roma where live music is playing in the piazza below our apartment, interspersed with church bells on the hour and in the distance fireworks can be seen dotting the ancient skyline. 2017 has been a year of extreme highs & lows in which iâ€™m extraordinarily grateful to all of you who follow me. you help make it possible to do what i love for a living and thatâ€™s something i do not take for granted in a world where thereâ€™s so much pain every day. iâ€™m choosing to focus on the good tonight, welcoming 2018 with hope. âœ¨ of course, a little sparkles never hurt either and my dress is courtesy of my 1 month trial of @renttherunway #rtrunlimited which iâ€™m choosing to support because their primary mission is to help end waste in the fashion industry with a multi tiered approach to still providing women with fashionable and fun clothing. more on that soon. #myrtrğŸ‘— as for the bubbles, provided by @onehope, who were founded by eight friends with a lofty vision: to create exceptional products that inspire people to indulge while doing good â€” supporting them helps them support so many others, that i canâ€™t help but want to make them part of every celebration now. through their profits, more than a million meals have been served to those who might otherwise go hungry, cancer research has been supported, trees have been planted and so much more has been accomplished to make the world a better place; all of it which you can read about via their site on the â€˜impactâ€™ page. #onehopewine ğŸ¾ iâ€™m not perfect but more than anything what i realized in 2017 is that i can do good with the choices i make every day, the products i buy & the businesses i support. iâ€™m not the resolution type but i do have goals and mine for 2018 is to spend more of my life than ever before trying to spread more love than hate in every way i can. whatâ€™s your plan for this next year?

__label__Namibia swipe across to check out 7 of my favourite pics from my namibia trip with @landrover!âš¡ï¸ this trip was so unique and incomparable to anything i've done before. it was amazing to experience the unique landscapes of namibia from the drivers seat. not only did i experience diverse parts of a new country, but i learned new off road driving skills (the best part was cruising down the beach as you may remember from my stories!)
we got off the beaten track away from the tourist crowds whilst at the same time staying in luxurious different lodges each night.
this trip was fast paced and we saw so much in just one week - the land rover experience was truly the best way to see the country and get most out of the time i had.

highlights: ~ n/a'an wildlife sanctuary where we went for a walk with 2 rescued cheetahs!
~ 'glamping' under the stars in spitzkoppe, surrounded by an insane mars like landscape.
~ quad biking in swakopmund, home to the famous dunes by the ocean.
~ sleeping in the middle of the namib desert for 2 nights where we star gazed with their in house astronomer (we rigged the camera to his telescope to get that moon shot!)
~ waking up early to walk amongst the sossusvlei dunes and the dead trees.

__label__Banff,Alberta we got a 10 minute break from the gloomy weather as the sun broke through the clouds and lit up the trees and water. a few minutes later it was gone for the rest of the day. photography is much about being in the right place at the right time, but over the years iâ€™ve learned to appreciate the beauty in how the changing weather transforms a scene. i used to expect the best sunset and color every time i went out to shoot and the disappointment of things not living up to these expectations would ruin the experience for me. you canâ€™t worry about things out of your control and learning to travel with lower expectations has been the key to being pleasantly surprised more often than not. a few years ago i wouldâ€™ve left when i saw it was cloudy, but iâ€™m glad i stuck around this time to see what could happen.

__label__Amsterdam,Netherlands we saw these comically tiny canta cars parked on amsterdamâ€™ sidewalks, didnâ€™t know what to make of them, and finally decided to search for more info on them.. it turns out there super useful and have a very specific and thoughtful purpose. .
from wikipedia: the canta is a two-seat microcar from the netherlands specifically created for disabled drivers. it is classified as a mobility aid because the width of the vehicle is only 1.10 metres, thus it may - unlike larger microcars - be used on cycle paths as well as sidewalks and footpaths; in addition a driver's license is not required.

each canta is built with the adaptations required by the customer, such as locating controls and switches on the left or right side, or all on the steering wheel. seats have a wide range of adjustment and can swivel to ease entry and exit. instead of having a driver's seat, the "ride-in canta" (inrij canta) model is designed so that a wheelchair user can enter by a ramp at the rear and drive while seated in their wheelchair. the rear of the vehicle is lowered to the ground when parked and is raised pneumatically when the engine is started.

__label__Budapest,Hungary budapest is a city on either side of the majestic danube: buda, with its romantic streets and alleyways, and pest, an effervescent cultural centre. 
divided in two by the danube, the city is made up of buda on one side: with ottoman-era thermal baths at the foot of the spectacular gellÃ©rt hill, the royal palace and matthias church, it radiates calm and peace. one the other side lies pest, vibrant and lively, with its slew of museums rich in cultural and historical treasures, extraordinary secessionist architecture, its majestic parliament building considered as one of the most magnificent in the world, saint stephenâ€™s basilica surrounded by pedestrian streets, and its entirely renovated jewish quarter and palace district. the budapest eye is city's new attraction which came into operation since 2015. this 65 meters high is one of the largest mobile ferry wheel in europe and in the evening it offers a magical ride full of colors and stunning landscapes of budapest.
i will keep putting more pics from budapest soon..!!

__label__India happy 70th independence day, india ğŸ‡®ğŸ‡³
.
.
70 years on, here's the irony of our country: we drive the world's fanciest cars but don't see eye to eye with the man trying to make a living in the sultry heat or biting cold. we eat gourmet international food but bargain with the vegetable seller who walks for miles to get fresh produce. we have world class kitchens and culinary gadgets, but don't eat on the same table as the people we employ to cook in them. we've overrun our towns with ugly concrete construction but we only need to go to the outskirts to see dancing peacocks and running chinkara. the entrance to opulent havelis owned by millionaires is lined with open, stinking sewers. we say our religions forbid cruelty towards animals, yet we guiltlessly devour their milk and meat. we complain of racism abroad, but are racist towards our own countrymen...
.
.
i could go on, but here's the thing. we're some of the luckiest people on earth to be born amid the incredible natural beauty, wildlife and cultural diversity of india. 70 years on, can we stop the faux patriotism and pledge today to treat our fellow humans and animals and nature like they belong to this country - and this earth - too? ğŸ¤”
.

__label__Bali,Indonesia let's talk parental support. who here has parents that are furious with your career path or would be extremely disappointed if you chased your dreams?

i'm always very transparent about my nigerian upbringing and its strict guidelines for our lives - where you're either a doctor, a lawyer, or a disappointment.

it's both a cultural and generational disconnect when your elders hold onto very traditional ideas of what defines success.

they also want nothing more than for their kids to be financially set and afforded opportunities they never had, so they hold the practice of medicine or law as the holy grail of adulthood.

other things they also admire, masters degrees, marriage in your 20s, kids in your 30s, buying them a car in your 40s, retiring them in your 50s, and you better not gain a single pound or acquire acne from the stress of unrealistic expectations in the process ğŸ™ƒ

over the last 5 years, my mom has lectured me several times about how this "hobby" of blogging is useless and will never get me anywhere, and in typical aries fashion i used that to fuel me even more.

obviously we all want nothing more than to make our parents proud (my dad passed away two weeks before my first international trip in 2012 but he was 10x stricter than my mother, so just imagine), but there will come a sad day in life where both your parents will no longer be around.

and if you spent all those years doing nothing but trying to make them happy, what will you be left with when they're gone?

all of a sudden, that pride that you made them happy is short-lived when you go to sleep every night hating your life and wishing you could have pursued what you really loved.

at the end of the day, there are two people who i'm aiming to please. the woman in the mirror and the man upstairs.

anybody after that is just a bonus.

but your happiness isn't just defined by a career path. it's a life-long journey that your passions and sense of fulfillment in this world shapes daily.

the saddest life isn't the one who dies prematurely. it's the one who lived a full and long life for the approval of someone else.

your happiness is always worth pursuing. i hope this spoke to someone today â¤

__label__Washington we stopped at a ranger station to acquire a backcountry permit and were reminded to camp only on dirt and rocks, absolutely no foliage. when we arrived, we scoured the area and found just one obvious campsite. all dirt, lined with rocks. but even then, we dropped our packs and continued to roam around in search for additional options. we brought the required bear canister and blue bags for human waste. we did all the things, and yet... i havenâ€™t wanted to post this image because iâ€™m confident the first thing that will come to some folks minds is â€œthatâ€™s not 200 feet from the water!â€ and that wouldnâ€™t be an inaccurate statement - iâ€™m pretty sure it wasnâ€™t. itâ€™s definitely farther from the water than this image makes it appear... but thatâ€™s the fun and sometimes difficult part about photography.
.
lnt are guidelines that all of us wilderness lovers should know and practice. but the stars donâ€™t always align where you can check all the boxes. so do the best you can. good campsites are found, not made. clearing out an area, farther from the water would have done far more damage to this fragile place than taking up residency in an already existing spot closer to the lake.
.
but the point of this post is... thereâ€™s a lot of flack these days, people and accounts being reported and blasted for outdoor ethics or lack thereof. iâ€™m in full support of respecting and protecting the environment, following the rules, and putting those things above myself and my images... but itâ€™s good to remember this; a simple image doesnâ€™t usually tell a complete story.

__label__Iceland well iceland... you've been amazing, but this hike was easily one of the highlights of the trip. @chelseakauai and i met @joe_shutter and @frankframesthings on our third day, by chance, while finishing up lunch and we got to chatting... and a couple days later, we met up again and they took us out to this incredibly special place.
.
this trip was wonderful because we never really had a set agenda. sure, we had an idea of some of the places we wanted to go and the things we wanted to see, but the best memories weren't created at those iconic icelandic viewpoints that everyone has seen a thousand times. they happened when we chose to be spontaneous. i saw such a tiny fraction of what iceland had to offer, but i definitely experienced enough to know that i want to come back and experience so much more.
.
.
.

__label__Iceland this is another favorite photo of me. i was actually pretty terrified to get close to this icelandic horse which is ironic because horses were my favorite animal growing up. i have a weird fear when it comes to touching or being near horses. to me they feel like giants that could bite my entire hand off and eat it like a delicious apple(yes iâ€™m being dramatic). but when i was researching iceland the horses were a huge deal and i knew that when i arrived i needed to see one in person, which wasnâ€™t too hard because they were everywhere. when the time came to be face to face with one i was nervous but this specific black horse in this photo walked up to me with no fear and i think i was inspired by its bravery because without skepticism as soon as the horse was inches away from me i placed my hand on its face and my sister snapped this photo. it was a quick moment but a moment thatâ€™ll last forever. #iceland

__label__Bangkok,Thailand flying dong at wat saketğŸ¯
locals prefer to travel by canal ferry as itâ€™s faster (bangkok traffic can be too much) and cheaper so i gotta try this mode of transportation here in canals and i love it! no traffic jams, see more locals and also itâ€™s off the typical tourist trail. .
wat saket or the golden mount temple built on an artificial hill is not a popular with buddhists and tourists. the base of wat saket is an unusual cemetery built covered in vines and overgrown trees, it emits a rather spooky out-of-era vibe. perhaps this is because in the late 18th century, wat saket served as the capital's crematorium and the dumping ground for some 60,000 plague victims. approaching the top of the hill, you will be welcomed by a wall of bells and panoramas of historic bangkok.
.

__label__Greece i used to think that we had one soul mate that we would marry, spend the rest of our lives, and live happily ever after with.
â €â €â € â €
perhaps that's true for a select few, but i've found that in today's society, this view on love is not realistic.
â €â €â € â €
you can spend a lifetime with someone and reach a point where you don't even feel like you know them, or you can spend 24 hours and understand that person in ways that no one else could before that moment.
â €â €â € â €
sometimes, two souls just recognize each other. when that synchronicity happens, our hearts crack open, we are pushed to challenge ourselves and our expectations, and we grow further into our ideal selves.
â €â €â € â €
i've begun to measure my love not by time or space, but rather by intensity. it's not a matter of "will i marry this person" anymore. instead, it's "can i love with an open heart in this time we have together?"
â €â €â € â €
my travels have taught me that nothing is forever. but just because not all love is permanent, it doesn't mean it cannot be lived fully while it's there.
â €â €â € â €
love with an open heart, bask in the incredible intimacy of human connection, and do not be afraid to let go when that love has run its course.
â €â €â € â €
when it's meant to be, it will return.
â €â €â € â €
when it's not, it will make you stronger.
â €â €â € â €
love like it's forever. each moment holds with it a piece of eternity.
â €â €â € â €

__label__Prague,CzechRepublic i have fond memories of this grainy old shot of prague in 2007.
this was the first time i ventured into eastern europe, and i was pretty excited! it was a rough start - crossing by bus from germany into czech republic, i was the only one pulled off the vehicle for a little extra attention. 
the authorities thought i had overstayed in the schengen zone, because i was never stamped coming through the tunnel from u.k to france, thus i only had an entry stamp from the u.k. i eventually managed to convince them otherwise, thankfully. i never have the best relationships with border authorities, but more stories on that will come soon! 
the funny thing about this situation is my best friend who was traveling with me throughout 2007 had exactly the same stamps (or lack of) as me...and he remained comfortably warm inside the bus! ğŸ˜†ğŸ›ƒ

__label__MexicoCity,Mexico i think every time you visit a new place you meet a different side of yourself, and if you like the direction it makes you grow, you canâ€™t help but come back for water. mexico city has always brought out the lightest version of me; the one who laughs at nothing and doesnâ€™t care about her tangled hair or mangled spanish. when i say i miss a place, of course i miss its sounds and culture and food and people. but i think what i miss most is the girl i left there, a me who is deserving of nostalgia, or even better, a concerted effort to pull her out of my memories and into the present. iâ€™m sure iâ€™ll be back here soonâ€“ itâ€™s hard to resist a place that brings out all your favorite traits in complementary measures. but until then, to this girl; to the people she met, to the places she went, and to the tacos she photographed.

__label__Madrid,Spain day 202:
â€¢madridâ€¢
way more chilled out than barcelona, spotlessly clean and chocked full of parks and gorgeous little flower shops like this one, we enjoyed our day trip to madrid immensely! .
after an exhausting day with the pack in toledo yesterday we managed to find an incredibly safe place to park in central madrid and left the dogs for a few hours whilst alex and i had date day in the city. we havenâ€™t ever left the dogs before and it didnâ€™t feel very nice so we are unlikely to do it again but our quiet, relaxing walk arm in arm through the streets made us realise how much easier and less stressful this trip would have been if we didnâ€™t already have merlin and rupert. that being said we would never have taken this road trip if they werenâ€™t in our lives and would have instead gone backpacking so pluses and minuses!
.
our stroll took us past the absolutely ginormous royal palace that has over 3500 rooms (although only a stingy 15 for tourists) and dominates the skyline as it sprawls along the acropolis. we then had some tasty tapas in the historic mercado de san miguel including olives, paella and potatoes skewers! .
by now we were missing our family so we walked back via the charming plaza mayor to find monday where we parked her in a stunning park near the templo de debod which was a gift to spain from egypt! .
after lots of happy greetings from our boys (and now girl) i whipped up some mango pineapple smoothies and we all walked up to the park and sat on a bench for a couple of hours drinking our smoothies, people watching and listening to a saxophonist who suddenly appeared as the sun was beginning to set. it was pure magic. .
tomorrow we wake early and have a driving day all the way up to bilbao, stopping on the way for water etc. we have a few days exploring the area including san sebastiÃ¡n before we head into france. we donâ€™t want to go to early, we are still anxiously evading the cold. itâ€™s not going to last though, that much we know! .
.

__label__Havana,Cuba one of the coolest things about cuba is that every car is essentially a taxi driver. hitchhiking is also really common/easy here for that exact reason.

these are called collective taxis (taxi colectivos) and for less than $1, you can get yourself a few blocks/minutes down the road.

of course these cars are dated, but they still run like whistles, built for fashion and function.

but it definitely took me a few days to stop reaching for seat belts that were never there, lol.

one time when i reached over for the seat belt while in the front of a taxi, he laughed and said, "this is cuba... no belt, no problem!" jesus take the wheel. #literally

__label__Bali,Indonesia iâ€™m going to tell you a secret.
â €â €â € â €
i have these three personal stories. whenever someone gets close and wants to know more about me, i whip them out, so they can feel satisfied by my openness and vulnerability. so they can stop asking for more.
â €â €â € â €
butâ€¦ iâ€™ve told these stories a million times. i donâ€™t feel the pain anymore. i could have just as easily told you what i had for lunch.
â €â €â € â €
you see, to get up close and personal with somebodyâ€¦ itâ€™s terrifying.
â €â €â € â €
it means exposing myself. my vulnerabilities. my fears. my insecurities.
â €â €â € â €
so i package my â€œvulnerabilityâ€ stories, i hand one out to whoever gets too close, and secretly hope itâ€™s enough for them.
â €â €â € â €
but for the people who truly understand me, itâ€™s not enough.
â €â €â € â €
because they know that itâ€™s not the moments that i pose or prepare for that define me. itâ€™s those in between.
â €â €â € â €
my vulnerability still hides between the lines of my stories, suspended in the off-guard moments when i think that no one is watching.
â €â €â € â €
this is my weakness. and i share it with you, so that it may see the light.
â €â €â € â €

__label__Stockholm,Sweden i like to be proven wrong. maybe thatâ€™s why travel has become such a fundamental part of me: wherever i go, my preconceptions are challenged. i push myself to look beyond what i thought was true.
â €â €â € â €
thatâ€™s what happened in sweden.
â €â €â € â €
i was pretty â€œmehâ€ before coming here, mostly because i had heard that the swedes were:
â €â €â € â €
- extremely reserved
- super shy
- conflict avoidant
- only themselves when they got drunk
â €â €â € â €
ok, there was some truth behind these warnings (especially the last one haha) but what i found - pretty much right away - was so much more.
â €â €â € â €
once i cracked through their initial faÃ§ade, the swedes i interacted with had a soft, gentle kindness. as a collective, i found them to be independent, very open-minded, with a good sense of humor (witty af), and extremely calm. if i had to describe them in one word, it would be: unflappable.
â €â €â € â €
as a non-swedish friend living in stockholm told me: "swedes are like a frozen lake. once you crack the top layer, you'll see there is so much depth and beauty inside."
â €â €â € â €
i couldnâ€™t have found this to be more true. in other wordsâ€¦
â €â €â € â €
i love you, sweden!
â €â €â € â €

__label__ChiangMai,Thailand i don't own anything that comes even remotely close to equaling the price of my freedom to live where and how i please.

i struggled so much to get to this point, especially as an adolescent. and if i knew those phases were only preparing me for this, i'd do it all over again in a heartbeat.

you might be going through a troubling phase in life, and wondering if you'll ever see a light at the end of the tunnel.

and once you do, you realize it's just an oncoming train ğŸ˜­ğŸšˆ but trust me when i say the best way to build the mental capacity to develop the better part of your being, is to go through these trials and hardships. hate them but embrace them. we all have our struggles no matter where we are in life.

we also all have the same 24 hours in a day to decide to do something about them. let the thought of your breakthrough be the reason you break through.

there's a better you on the other side, i promise. not sure who i wrote this for, but something was tugging on my heart to share. â¤

__label__Copenhagen my time in denmark really got me thinking about the meaning of â€œcontentment.â€
â €â €â € â €
itâ€™s a word thatâ€™s thrown around a lot here. the danes are all about living in the present, being satisfied with what they have (after all, â€œit could be worseâ€), and have a sort of â€œif itâ€™s not broken, donâ€™t fix itâ€ mentality.
â €â €â € â €
clearly something is working for them - theyâ€™re one of the happiest countries in the world, and the societal structure theyâ€™ve built for themselves works.
â €â €â € â €
while i find this general contentment with life quite beautiful, i also have qualms with it. it may not be broken, but what if thereâ€™s something that works even better? and if you are used to everything working smoothly, do you get too comfortable in that security and certainty? what if youâ€™re truly unhappy and want to make a change in your life - will that contentment transform into complacency and fear of uncertainty? â €â €â € â €
i am not saying that one mindset is better than the other - itâ€™s incredible to witness a society who collectively feels so content. personally, i always strive for more and find it hard to feel satisfied with â€œthe way things areâ€ for too long. i want to learn the art of contentment so i can happily slow down, but i also fear getting â€œstuckâ€ in it and not making the transformations i wish to see in my life.
â €â €â € â €
what do you guys think? where is the line between contentment and complacency?

__label__BuenosAires,Argentina okay, i couldn't resist posting this! this is a throwback to a few days ago when i did my urban adventures food tour of buenos aires. there were 8 of us on the tour and i really can't recommend it enough, we were very well fed! we started with empanadas and then went to a local restaurant for bbq meat and salad (as a vegetarian i had a pasta dish) followed by the best gelato ever and finished with local drink "mate". if you do ever get gelato in argentina make sure you get the dulce de leche flavor. it's a signature sweet here and it's delicious, like a more delicious caramel than any caramel you've ever had! @helloworldau #expertsineverywhere

__label__Milan,Italy these are my hosts in #milan: federico (@effescuolo), michael (@michaelcastorino), giuseppe (@gc53), and the pup is chuck. respectively, their dreams are to live doing what he loves in a tranquil place; to become a successful actor; and to see his father again; (i don't speak dog, but i assume chuck's dream is to always be well-fed and cuddled). i was warmly welcomed by these guys from the moment i walked into their apartment. we share a best friend, and, by extension, they instantly made me feel like a friend as well. i was most pleasantly taken aback by their love for one another: they are childhood friends who have lived together for years, yet still make the time to frequently sit down for family dinners and support each other at the drop of a hat. their friendship runs like a well-oiled machine, and it is inspiring. 
these guys renewed my belief that friendships are one of the purest, most noble possessions that we can acquire in our lifetime. people, things, jobs... they come and go. the few humans who remain by our side and support us through the highs and the lows, however, are worth every ounce of our love and loyalty. friendship is a pact, and those who truly commit to it, do not lose it. #thenomadsoasisproject #celinnesoasis

__label__Florence,Italy it feels like it was just yesterday. i was a junior in college, boarding a flight all alone to italy, my mom was holding me and bawling (seriously she wouldnâ€™t let me go ğŸ˜‚), and i was a complete mess. i got on the plane and proceeded to cry for a solid 3 hours in to the flight. i voraciously journaled my feelings, ate way too many brownies, and watched â€œeat, pray, loveâ€ in an attempt to get it together.
_
looking back, i was a little overly dramatic and i quote per my italy journal, â€œi just keep picturing myself crying alone in my room at night hating my decision to come over here.â€
_
lol i mean, i was going to italy for crying out loudâ€”- but, it was terrifying at the time. a new place, a new school, i didnâ€™t know anyone, and just being away from home for a whole semester had me all up in my feelings. ahhh my sweet little 21 year old self.
_
itâ€™s honestly funny looking back on it now, knowing that studying abroad was one of the best experiences of my life. it completely took me out of my comfort zone and helped me grow and mature so much as a person and an artist.
_
i love florence so much for that reason alone, and because it really changed everything for me.
_
this summer, i am so ready to head back there again, but this time for a new reason! i get to teach a group of you all in the studio that i learned at, all those years ago!! iâ€™m sure i will have all the same nervous feelings, but i just love the butterflies you get when boarding a flight to go somewhere or do something youâ€™ve never done before.
_
i hope you all will join me on this new adventure!! i have a few spots left and they are open to anyone and everyone who is interested in creating, exploring and meeting other inspiring people!
_
for more information on my florence, italy painting retreat, head to the link in my bio! iâ€™d love to be your personal travel agent and host you all in my favorite place ever! i can already taste the gelato nowğŸ¨!! #kaylaweberartgoesabroad

__label__Dublin,Ireland just a simple window reflection with the focus point set on the @thetemplebarpub. took a few attempts with this as it was shot handheld at 1/50 shutter speed so i had to be very steady with my hands to eliminate shake. then with the iso pushing 1600 i knew i was risking some noise if i  pushed any further. aperture was f2.8 and focal length 24mm. its certainly not perfect but i am not chasing perfection. we all worry so much when we start sharing photos online and getting feedback on them instantly. we are free to create whatever we want as much or as little as we want. doesn't matter if someone doesn't like it. they don't have to. you do. don't let anything hold you back from your dreams or your content on your page. the only person you are really playing against is yourself. as long as you accept that and understand that you don't need to compare yourself to anyone else you will be ultimately free. get that photo that's sitting on your hard drive for ages that you like, get it edited and post it tonight. don't put it off. don't even wait for the "golden hour" just get it up and share your work. too many of us are holding back thousands of amazing photos, videos and creations because we fear what others think. remember that in decades from now this will all be a memory. go out there today or whenever you are ready and create your history ğŸ’ª don't wait too long cause in a flash it will all be over. â¤ï¸

4 feb 2019.
.
sri lanka achieved independence from the great britain in 4 feb 1948, and today is her 71st independence day.
.
every year during the national day celebration, the president of sri lanka would invite leaders from other countries to come in and join him & his people in the celebration held at galle face. this year, the president of maldives & his wife graced the event as guests of honour, while last year it was prince edward of england. elaborate army parade, cultural performances and festivities were organised nationwide to mark the occasion.
.
we didnâ€™t go out to town until after the main parade was done at around noon. so no photos of the main event taking place today.
.
happy 71st independence day, sri lanka.

__label__Iceland wanted to thank everyone for all the support youâ€™ve given me in my photography career and all the kind comments you leave on pics/videos. iâ€™ve been thinking a lot lately about this wild path instagram has taken me down and what the future will look like. iâ€™m very early into my photography career and lately been finding my interests drifting towards tech, startups, and projects in those industries. thatâ€™s one of the reasons getting involved with @explorest has been such a fun venture for me. one of the reasons i left electrical engineering was i felt the experiences i was having traveling, meeting incredible people, and seeing places i had only dreamed of visiting, outweighed the benefits of my position at the time. the road has been wild and one of the better decisions iâ€™ve made. the thing i tell people i miss most about my old job is the intellectual stimulation, feeling of building something on a team, and working towards a common goal. traveling and sharing the world through my eyes will do for now but i got my eyes fixed on the horizon for the next big thing. sorry this turned into a diary entry/resume but hope me sharing my thoughts from time to time helps provide a little bit more insight into the person behind the pictures. would love to hear more about what you guys do and your backgrounds!

__label__Queenstown,NewZealand so, as i mentioned last month when i went scuba diving, i'm kind of scared of water. can't you tell? ğŸ˜‚
.
despite the sheer look of terror on my face (which i had to share, because it's hilarious), river-boarding in queenstown was actually riveting. the experience reminded me of a lesson i've learned repeatedly during my travels: we cannot let our fears dictate how we live our lives.
.
was i nervous about river-boarding? yes. did that stop me from doing it? no. one of my favorite moments was when i was spinning around in a whirlpool, starting to freak out, and the instructor said: "just let it spin you and you'll come right out. don't fight it."
.
ain't that right. sometimes life will spin you around relentlessly, and you have a choice: fear and fight the process, or stay calm and have faith that you'll get out of it eventually. either way, you're there... so it's up to you to enjoy the ride.
.
huge thanks to the amazing crew at serious fun riverboarding for making me feel safe and taken care of (and for the hysterical photos)!
.

__label__Ubud this is grandpa (real name is made marka, but he goes by grandpa), one of my hosts in ubud, bali. grandpa also happens to be a balinese priest and a spiritual healer (for those of you who watched/read "eat, pray, love," he was in the same class/trained by the same high priest as ketut and knew him well).
.
i was invited to come stay in a house in the middle of a village about 2km from central ubud. smack dab in the middle of the famous rice fields, my accommodation was very simple: we're talking squatty toilet with a manual flush, bucket showers, cows, pigs, and roosters who woke me up at 4:30 am with their crows. despite the lack of luxuries, i didn't want to leave that place - my time there, soaking up the calm and peace of that environment, renewed me to my core. .
.
grandpa didn't speak a word of english, yet we somehow managed to have some deep conversations. with the help of my other hosts, who translated, i was taught about the balinese philosophy of leading with your heart versus your mind (post on that coming up). i learned that each of us is born with a brother and a sister, spiritual entities who know what you need even when you're not aware and don't want to admit it. these "siblings" - represented by the placenta - use their energy to help you meet the people who can help you throughout your life.
.
the sheer power of grandpa's presence healed me. i understood so much about myself, much of which i'm till processing and will share this week. my time in that house was yet another reminder that understanding someone goes far, far beyond the spoken word. we are all connected, and once we tap into the energy of that network... that's when we begin to understand that god is but one force, split amongst 7+ billion.
.

__label__Mumbai,Maharashtra as a common sandpiper amused me and my camera while strolling in the jogger's park around the vashi holding pond, a jogger saw me taking photographs of the bird and asked me:

jogger: hi, do you want to take photographs of a snake?
nitsbee: yes, of course! why not?
jogger(smiling and pointing to the shrubs a little ahead from where we were standing): there it is among the bushes. it has come out now. you can find it there.
nitsbee: ohh cool! thanks.

i still couldn't see the snake and walked a little ahead towards the shrubs to where the jogger pointed out. i stood steady and glanced everywhere on the grounds to find the snake. suddenly saw some dried foliage moving on the ground just 5 meters from where i was standing and saw the snake slithering past me. "click click click went my camera". other joggers saw me and were curious as to why i was pointing my camera towards the ground and they realised it was a snake. soon, other joggers gathered around to see the snake. the snake slithered away soon into the dense foliage and disappeared. plenty of shots that i took. i realised it was the first time that i've ever photographed a snake. wasn't even on my bucket list. couldn't identify the snake but my best guess is that it is rat snake. let me know the correct species if i'm wrong. .
.
.
.
1/1600s : f/6.5 : iso 800

__label__Kyoto,Japan after the initial high of getting lucky enough to see the sakura in bloom in japan, i felt pretty overwhelmed. by their extravagant beauty, by the crowds everywhere i tried to go, by the pressure to photograph them like everyone else and in knowing that this beauty is just fleeting... .
.
after running around for a day in kyoto, trying to glimpse the sakura in places everyone said i couldnâ€™t miss and failing to get a quiet moment with these beauties, i stopped. this isnâ€™t how i like to travel, i remembered. .
.
so the next morning, i ditched the bus pass, borrowed a bicycle from my japanese host and just wandered around the streets with no particular place in mind. in a neighbourhood park, where locals were jogging and walking their dogs, i finally found the connection i was looking for. the inspiration to sit under a cherry tree, gaze at the fleeting beauty and pen fleeting thoughts in my notebook. .
.
i think the key to really savouring your travels (and life) is being you. chasing your bliss and not someone elseâ€™s ğŸ¾
.

__label__Dubrovnik,Croatia my first day in #dubrovnik, i decided to take the cable car up the mountain to see the sunset and city from above. little did i know it would turn into a spectacular memory. in addition to the sunset being stunning (expected), there were so many wild horses! i spotted one in the distance and decided to follow it, and eventually it led me to the others. en route i made a buddy, who was also photographing the horses. together we trekked through the landscape - it began getting dark quite quickly as the sky prepared for a massive thunderstorm. it was like something out of a movie: exploring on top of dubrovnik, overlooking the poetic #oldcity, watching wild horses roam as lighting and thunder struck in the background. it was quite idyllic prior to me running back to the cable car and getting soaked, of course.
but so worth it.
moments like these remind me why a life of travel is the way ğŸ¤—

__label__ZionNationalPark the infamous subway hike in zion...one of my favorite hikes we've done this year. technically called the left fork of north creek canyon, it is much better known for its resemblance to an underground subway. we did what is called the bottom-up route, which is basically hiking through the river to get to the subway (rather than the top-down approach, which involves rappelling down into the canyon). whichever way you go, the end goal is this beautiful scene right here. this long cylindrical tunnel of sandstone has to be one of zion's more interesting geological features. it is a lot of fun to photograph as well. if you are thinking of doing the subway hike or rappel, make sure you get a permit at the nps wilderness office

__label__Thailand [i can't make this up] what inspires me to write is just memories from the past. everything comes from things iâ€™ve been through. sometimes it can be just me seeing things other people have been through that i could relate to. itâ€™s not always just about my memory. so i create an image in my head. someone recently said to me â€œyou smile so often in your snaps, are there ever any bad days?â€ like you and everyone else whoâ€™s reading, iâ€™m human. my bad days, however, are really bad. i experience a lot of frustration. sometimes when iâ€™m writing these journals i donâ€™t want to remember my past.. the streets, the rejection, the shame. then i donâ€™t want to be selfish and not tap into the realness of my life. to ease my way out of frustration is by writing it out and creating art. itâ€™s really hard to describe how i feel when i take a photo or when iâ€™m out on the road. itâ€™s just a temporary get away from the problems, and you know.. thatâ€™s good enough for me. and then when i really think about it i guess iâ€™m doing ok for someone that was labeled â€œspecial edâ€ and below reading level? although my writing isnâ€™t perfect, i can admit now that itâ€™s gradually gotten better. kinda. for those of you guys who spend the time to read these long captions that i write it truly does mean a lot. iâ€™ve always had the problem of over thinking and putting myself out there to the world. but i had to really look at myself in the mirror and remind myself that i donâ€™t ever want to be scared to tell my story. so i hope that by reading this that you feel comfortable enough to even share yours. either with me in the comments below or even in a dm. iâ€™ll be your pen pal, your homie from the cyberwebz. since you made it this far if you're feeling this let me know by commenting #fammmm.

__label__NewZealand my whole life iâ€™ve always been told that my face reads like an open book. unable to hide my feelings and emotions, what you see is what you get. can you tell what iâ€™m thinking here? if youâ€™re first guess was â€œfuck mornings, give me coffeeâ€ then yes, you are correct. but itâ€™s also much more than this. as i look at my face in this picture, it really sums up the past few months for me. iâ€™m chronically exhausted, stressed to the max and beyond tired, and yet trying to find a little glimmer of something to make me smile, which is harder every day. burnt out doesnâ€™t begin to cover it. with my insomnia back in full swing, my anxiety keeping me company every waking hour, and a punishing travel schedule that i just couldnâ€™t say no to, i only blame myself for getting to this point.  living in a competitive world if youâ€™re not â€œbusyâ€ or â€œgreatâ€ than youâ€™re lazy and unsuccessful, and the pressure of this path iâ€™ve been on is often suffocating, and it often feels like my creativity has gone forever. without realizing it, iâ€™ve slipped into the habit of only showing the glamor of travel, of my world. normally i would have posted a different version of this shot, where my tired face is hidden or later on when iâ€™ve had 3 coffees and put on makeup, perhaps with an inspirational caption about following your dreams. but part of me has always been an honest cynic, and iâ€™m tired. iâ€™m tired of everything. here is a moment of reality. i look and feel like shit, but iâ€™m trying to do my best and do my job. i love it but itâ€™s hard. we are all imperfect humans full of complex emotions, me included. you are not alone. now where is the coffee? #inspirationalandallthatshit #lookwhatthecatdraggedin
