__label__Bali today, in the little village of gobleg in the hills of munduk, i met a traditional balinese healer (locally called a balian). he is a farmer, but several years ago, people realized that his massages were healing. when someone in the village has muscle aches or broken bones, they don't go to the hospital; they go to him first.
.
.
when i asked him how long since the realization, he laughed and said he doesn't even know how old he is! there were no records back in the day, and many balinese elders don't know when their birthday is. i'd peg him at 80-90 years, but he's still very fit and has happy lines on his face ğŸ‘€
.
.
he gave me a healing massage, and at first, i was quite tensed about how it would turn out. then he massaged the tension points in my head and i felt light as a feather and tuned in to his constant chatting (in balinese though). he said something about india, something about yoga, something about the stresses i'm carrying around. meeting him was inexplicably rejuvenating ğŸ˜‡
.
.
also gobleg, such a pretty little village with rice paddies, marigold fields and wild flowers ğŸ’™
.
.

__label__Dubrovnik,Croatia even though i write a lot about adventurous activities or bucket list experiences, one of my favorite things to do when i travel is actually pretty simple. there is nothing better than sitting outside at a cafe anywhere in europe when it's warm and sunny outside; glass of wine and snacks included of course. i don't know why, but being a part of this communal activity is so relaxing and so therapeutic for me that i relish any opportunity to enjoy it. now that summer is in full swing, i'm excited for my next trip starting this weekend as i board a flight for germany, but that's not what i want to share today, instead it's this image from the always amazing dubrovnik, croatia. 
the old town in dubrovnik can definitely get busy, but as late afternoon dissolves into early evening the streets clear out and you're left with this glittering city all to yourself. there's a reason why "game of thrones" uses it to film their king's landing shots, it feels like the city jumped out of a fantasy novel. 
walking down along the limestone-paved stradun - the main thoroughfare in town - i turned right and found this cafe near the rector's palace. in one scene, i had found everything i love about europe. it was a beautiful day, not too hot during the day or too chilly at night, and everyone was out and about enjoying the perfect weather while it lasted. this cafe in central dubrovnik was popular and with good reason. sitting there chatting with friends, enjoying a glass of crisp croatian white wine and spending hours people watching is the height of travel perfection. while the major attractions are always fun to visit, it's experiencing the laid back vibe of the mediterranean that's even more special; understanding the city by living it instead of just seeing it.

__label__Brussels,Belgium happy world nutella day to every chocolate-lovin, calorie-cravin, nutella consumer on this planet.

if there's one detail that's common knowledge to anyone who follows my blog, it's my borderline [understatement] obsession with this sinfully delicious goodness called nutella.

i couldn't let this day go by without paying homage to the hazelnut glory that jesus died for our sins to try and save us from.

my best nutella splurges came in belgium with my good friend @nicolasparise, on belgian waffles smothered with that royal cream for $1 and in romania, on cake bread (for 25 cents). ğŸ˜

however you're choosing to celebrate this sacred day, i just ask that you keep me in mind when baking your nutella recipes tonight ğŸ˜‚

while @nutella and i are still working through a partnership, i ask that you all make sure to double your usual consumption today.

thank you, nutella, for feeding me, comforting me, and helping me push my limits in life (mainly on the scale, but izall good). marry me, nutella, and let's just give the world the chocolate babies they deserve.

__label__Cusco,Peru for those of you who have been following me and @rickromaâ€™s lost camera/hat saga (we left them in a taxi and the driver never returned them), i am pleased to announce that we are finally reunited with our belongings!
â €â €â € â €
we seriously deserve a detective badge for our persistence in the past 3 days: we traveled back to sacred valley, scoured over video surveillance to identify the car, and worked with police to track down the driver. almost two whole days gone in this hunt, but we found him despite the slim odds!
â €â €â € â €
one of the policemen made an offhand comment that we â€œmust have such a bad impression of peruvians now.â€
â €â €â € â €
but the reality is quite the opposite. we may have encountered one naughty peruvian, but we befriended so many good ones because of it. during our fiasco, everyone - strangers on the street, hotel owners, policemen - went above and beyond to help us.
â €â €â € â €
i strongly believe that on the whole, people are good, and i was touched by the peruviansâ€™ kindness. yes, i have my critiques about these countries - aka itâ€™s true that a lot of locals try to rip people off because they are tourists - but in the end, i found myself surrounded by infinitely more good than bad.
â €â €â € â €
peru has for sure earned a special place in my heart!

__label__Delhi,India mornings are starting to become my favorite time of the day, and though 95% of the time i don't wake up to an alarm clock, i'm still an early riser because of the lifestyle i get to live.

i read a quote almost a decade ago, and it completely changed my perspective. "mondays don't suck; it's your life that does." whew, that stung. but oftentimes we're so busy getting offended that we don't let the conviction seep through and do its job.

so i started treasuring my mondays as much as my fridays, and my mornings as much as my evenings.

there's purpose and value in both. but i needed that quote to remind me of that.

what aspect of life are you taking for granted that you're working on changing? let's discuss!

__label__Petra,Ma`An,Jordan i was very honored to spend last week with @contiki x @treadright and activist @celinescousteau learning more about their mission to #maketravelmatter. each day we spent a portion seeing some of jordanâ€™s incredible historic sites (like this here in the ancient city of petra) while also visiting with some amazing women-owned cooperatives like iraq al amir.
.
i love travel. i think itâ€™s been one of the most important factors of growth in my life. but as more of us travel (and especially as i feel i often encourage travel), i often think about practical ways to make our collective impact a positive one. there is no one right approach, but i loved this trip so much because i got to see one possibility of what that might look like.
.
although treadright is a nonprofit, rather than focus on charity, it empowers its local partners with the tools to create viable tourism-based businesses and connects them to a larger network of tour operators (like @contiki). we got to do everything from cooking classes to ceramics, hiking, hand picking figs, and buying unique locally-sourced products. meeting the women of @iraqalamircoop and seeing their sense of pride and ownership over their many projects (among them: running a guest house for hikers on the jordan trail and hosting paper making classes) was equally as interesting and inspiring to me as seeing the windswept canyons of wadi rum.
.
pretty sure no one reads thoughts this longğŸ˜‚ but yea the intersection of all these things just makes me really excited!!â˜ºï¸
.
ps: i lost all my photos when my phone broke, but for now if youâ€™d like to see more of what we experienced please stop by my storyhighlight or the others on the trip for some really well written thoughts @treadright, @soultravelblog, @alisonsadventures and @celinescousteau. thank you all for an unforgettable trip. blog coming next week x

__label__Denver,Colorado exercise is a debt i owe loki and payments are due every day.
_
it could just be luck, but loki is the second northern breed iâ€™ve had that is surprisingly â€œchillâ€ and relatively well behaved.
and just by coincidence, i exercised the heck out of both of them.
when weâ€™re not on the road or backcountry skiing, loki gets his exercise in the suburbs by running next to a bike.
_
is it dangerous? yeah, a little. 
is running on pavement the best thing for his joints? maybe not. 
one thing i am certain of is that a lot more dogs die of obesity, anxiously escaping from backyards and getting hit by cars, or being put down due to behavioral problems, than dogs running on too much pavement. 
this is the best option i have for intense exercise living in the city.
_
i really donâ€™t care how you run your dog as long as your smart about it,
but i am here to tell you that you owe it to them.
_

__label__SanFrancisco,California every time i come back to the u.s. after several months or a couple years away, itâ€™s always a bittersweet feeling.

the immigration officer greeted me with the biggest smile, and then i heard the words i donâ€™t hear too often â€” â€œwelcome home.â€ little did he know, this was actually the closest iâ€™d get to returning â€œhomeâ€ in over 12 years ğŸ˜±

i drove down highways that led to the church my dad was a pastor at, the hospitals my mom was a nurse at, and where we'd exit to go to nigerian functions every weekend.

fast-forward to my senior year of college four years ago, and i knew leaving this country would be the best thing for me.

though i acknowledge my privilege of owning a first world passport that allows me to leave, i also recognize that same privilege that also allows me to come back.

it was 4am in argentina last november when i watched the final poll counts verify my worst nightmare.

i never felt more let down, betrayed, and disgusted by so many people.

i was numb and i took out my hatred for he who shall not be named and his supporters out on the entire country.

i dissociated myself with america and started referring to the state i was born rather than the country when foreigners would ask, hoping to deflect any conversation about how the heck we got ourselves in this mess. or as they would kindly ask, â€œwhat the hell is wrong with you guys over there?!â€ ğŸ™ƒ

but being back on u.s. soil now has reminded me of the beautiful, vibrant, and diverse souls that still populate this country.

san francisco is a microcosm of the progressiveness and potential this country is known for.

and all it really took were a couple strolls through target and best buy to forgive all sins if weâ€™re being really honest here. ğŸ˜­

this country is a work in progress. but what country isnâ€™t? its people are healing, hurting, learning, and growing. i am too.

though our differences make us unique, i hope we can unite in advocating for policy change, inclusion, and the never-ending fight against racism and all other forms of discrimination.

thanks @gopro for bringing me back! my liver hates/thanks you for all the fun.

__label__Bali,Indonesia every day i'm falling more in love with the woman i'm becoming, the dreams i'm pursuing, and the legacy i'll be leaving.

when i think about all the hurt, pain, regret, deceit, and struggle i've endured, it makes me even more grateful to be standing, dancing, and running down this path now.

everything you go through in life is setting you up for your best-selling story.

the story that gets passed on whenever your name is whispered in a room.

the story that gets shared at your wedding about the person someone fell in love with.

the story that gets a final ovation of praise in your obituary.

i can hardly tell you where i'll be or what i'll be doing next month, but i've learned to embrace that kind of spontaneity, and the beauty in that type of freedom.

my life is a manifestation of what can happen when a colorful imagination meets a type of hustle you can't put a price on.

there is so much more to come and @dakotaadan and i can hardly wait to show you guys more scenes from our time in bali.

special thanks to @theasia.collective for all their support and making all of this possible.

photo credit | @dakotaadan

watch the instastories for some more behind-the-scenes footage!

__label__UnitedStates friends...big news today! i can't tell you how happy i am to announce this new project. in celebration of the 2016 centennial of the u.s. national park service, i, along with @istefpayne, am embarking on an epic road trip in an #airstream trailer to visit and create incredible content in every one of the 59 u.s. national parks in 52 weeks (#59in52). that averages to just about one national park every 6 days...a crazy, but totally doable, goal. we will crisscross america in search of great photos, amazing stories, and whatever other trouble we can get in to. we will be kayaking across the @evergladesnps, rafting the @grandcanyonnps, photographing the bears catching salmon in @katmainps, hiking in @glaciernps, and capturing the incredible fall foliage in @acadianps (among many other experiences!). we will be sharing stories, photos, timelapse videos, and i will even be creating virtual reality 360 video in every park (for viewing on youtube or with a headset like @google cardboard). we are calling it the greatest american road trip, and will be sharing the content here as well as much more on our website: www.thegreatestroadtrip.com (link in bio). i urge you to visit our website and sign up for updates from us on the road. it's gonna be a wild and fun ride! please tag a friend or two who might like to follow this project as well. the mountains are indeed calling, and starting january 1, 2016 we are heeding that call. i hope you'll follow our journey .

__label__GrandCanyonNationalPark there's and old photographer saying that goes like this: bad weather makes for good photography. i think what this saying really means is that different, and often ominous, weather can add drama and interest to a photo that is otherwise not there on sunny and clear days. this is especially true in the grand canyon. if you are lucky enough to witness a storm over the canyon, be careful and watch for lightning, but by all means photograph the heck out of it. this was an epic storm that rolled in just around sunset. it was quite incredible to witness. i think the black and white better depicts the feeling i had while watching this storm

__label__Bali,Indonesia selamat hari kemerdekaan! happy independence day, indonesia!

i've found myself head over heels in love with this country - the only place i've ever been where i don't want to leave.

you know how hard it is to keep my perpetually-wandering @$% in one place?

indonesia has fulfilled every last desire and shown me the nirvana i never knew i needed.

the locals will smile, wave, greet, and take me in like one of their own, and besides swimming in a lap of luxury on the low, bali has reminded me that putting myself first is no longer an afterthought. it is necessary.

we cruised around bali admiring the thousands of flags draping the street, relaying our happiness through smiles and cheers to all the marches and parades that commemorated indonesian independence from the dutch in 1945.

indonesia holds such a special place in my heart, and i couldn't be happier to partake in the festivities celebrating the brilliance, vibrancy, and independence of indonesia ğŸ‡®ğŸ‡© p.s. more bootcamp and bahasa fun on my instastories!

__label__Dubai,UnitedArabEmirates for the first time in my life, i chased both the sunrise and the sunset in one day. i arrived to dubai at 4 am, and my host and i decided to watch the sun rise over the city. as you can see, i was not disappointed. 
iâ€™ve only been in dubai a short time, but i am already learning a lot about it. in dubai, there is no compromise when it comes to quality - the city boasts top-notch urban planning and the best of everything that money can buy. don't have a canal because it's in the middle of the desert? no problem, they irrigate one. don't have enough space? no problem, they build new islands. it's almost eery how much they manipulate nature here... almost everything is fake! even the seawater is filtered before it reaches the beach. 
this city strives to be the best, and this is clear by its extravagance and extreme attention to detail. 
as my host told me, "everyone is here for a reason, not for pleasure." people flock to dubai to make the big bucks and to have fun. it is a city that provides its people with everything they could possibly want, but not a place where you can stay in long-term if you are not a local. 
more thoughts to come on this... for now enjoy this sexy skyline, which is arguably nicer than new york city's ğŸ™Š. #dubai #visitdubai #dubailife #dubaistyle #dubaiblogger #mydubai #dubaitourism #unitedarabemirates #emirates

__label__CapeTown,WesternCape whenever someone asks me about my favorite places to travel, my mind invariably wanders to cape town, south africa. before my first visit there everyone told me that there was just something special about south africa; a kind of spirit that infects your soul in every positive sense of the term possible. they were right. itâ€™s a place i long to return to, even minutes after leaving and i know itâ€™s a city and country that will never lose its appeal to me.

i took this picture of cape townâ€™s iconic table mountain, one of the 7 new natural wonders of the world, from robben island, just across table bay from the city. itâ€™s a powerful place to visit for one important reason - it was the site of south africaâ€™s maximum security prison for political prisoners during apartheid. it was here were nelson mandela was imprisoned for 18 of the 27 years he served behind bars before the end of the appalling system of forced segregation known as apartheid. 
today itâ€™s one of cape townâ€™s most popular tourists spots, providing everyone with a powerful glimpse into a very dark period of south african history. former prisoners now serve as tour guides, sharing their personal stories of imprisonment on the lonely rock known as robben island.

to me both cape town and south africa are intensely beautiful places, but itâ€™s this subtext, this complicated personality that make them not just interesting to visit but, i believe, important to visit. #beautifuldestinations

__label__Havana,Cuba #sponsored â€¢ i love seeing data about travel and can geek out with the best of them when it comes to talking about trends so every year i look forward to the travel hacker guide from @kayak which shares information about places grouped by those that are top trending, the most popular overall, beach, wallet-friendly and more. because travel is my job and my passion, it helps if i stay up to date using tools like this and i think the guide is a great place for anyone to start their travel planning! for instance, i enjoyed learning that i have been to three of the top 5 trending places which are havana, reykjavik and bali, while the two places rounding out the list are destinations i personally want to visit in 2017; tokyo and auckland. in fact, auckland is featured in the #kayaktravelhacker twice. it's also listed as a top trending beach destination! i took this photo during our trip to havana and it is easy for me to understand why the city made the list. we just couldn't stop talking about it before we visited and haven't stopped thinking about it since we came home! for the next 24 hours, see the link in my profile for the full report from kayak.

__label__London,UnitedKingdom i hope you guys are ready to stroll down memory lane as i spend the next 7 days explaining a bit more of my journey and giving you small excerpts from what you can expect from my e-book, which... yes, in case you missed the memo, the pre-orders have opened and there are less than 50 left to claim your gift! details in bio!
____________________________________________

my first trip abroad came at the tender age of 22 to the uk. i was a super-senior at @bakeruniversity #noshame, and studying abroad was never really an option for me as i played collegiate basketball and season lasted from november clear through march. not really convenient to peace out on your teammates halfway through season.

but when i ended up changing majors, i was offset a whole year anyway. so i did what any responsible college student would do at that point, and tacked on another semester to prolong real-life responsibilities and adulthood while i casually set off to see the world.

my semester studying abroad at @harlaxton_college would turn into my first paid overseas gig upon graduation.

i remember the principal coming up to me the second week and saying, "i don't know what it is about you, but you're a force of nature, and i like it." and i made sure to make my presence known and felt.

i became a harlaxton ambassador, a harlaxton blogger, and a harlaxton resident assistant. putting myself in positions to prove my worth as an asset to the institution and subconsciously networking my way to my first job abroad, all while still being a student and traveling most weekends like the others.

a lot of people were quick to throw out the word "lucky". how "lucky" i was to get this opportunity while failing to realize luck is a mere byproduct of hard work. or at least its first cousin.

the harder you work, the "luckier" you seem to get, because when there's something you want bad enough, the universe conspires in your favor if you meet it halfway.

this comes from a chapter about landing jobs abroad and different opportunities that pay you to travel. get your pre-ordered copy from the link in bio! ğŸŒâœˆ

__label__Maldives meet the very small, but gorgeous bio-luminescence plankton. it wasn't in peak season, but we were blessed to see a few on the shores of our small island, in the darkness underneath a sky full of stars. how amazing his creations, how blessed we all are.

__label__Bali,Indonesia 2 years ago @laurareidd and i visited villa kubu for a media lunch to share the experience with our relatively small audience at the time. having traveled asia as broke backpackers for nearly 7 months, no meal had ever tasted so good. i distinctly remember @villakubu showing us the villas and i just stood there imagining what it would be like to stay the night. can't believe that 2 quick years later i got to find out. it's insane where the pursuit of passion can take you. so grateful for moments like this.

__label__GlacierNationalPark yesterday was sept 11 ... a day we all remember as a tragedy. but it's always been hard to remember it like that since i've always known it as a day to celebrate my dads birthday. i guess it is always a matter of perspective.. i've struggled with the concept of replacing a terrible memory with a positive one without losing empathy for those involved. maybe it's possible to do both. #911

__label__CapeTown,WesternCape there is power in redefining who you are through the beauty and culture of the motherland.

this is a necklace from the zulu tribe in south africa, which uses colors and shapes to communicate, especially in regards to relationship status.

the green signifies contentment and bliss.
the blue embodies faithfulness.
the white conveys my need for love.
the yellow encompasses wealth.
and the black represents marriage.

every day i find a new way to be humbled, enlightened, and liberated through exploring a continent where the people, as much as their stories, beauty, and pride, move me to tears.

though the media shoved poverty porn down the western world's throats for the majority of our lives, it didn't mean that the opportunity to go re-learn what makes the motherland shine, would be a question left for the imagination.

travelers, curious souls, and everyone in between, i dare you to visit this continent and re-write the pages of a story that is left blank, torn up, or crossed out in far too many history books.

after all, every 60 seconds, a minute passes in africa ğŸ˜Œ 
#africathroughmyeyes
#africathroughmywords

__label__SanDiego,California life is a rollercoaster. itâ€™s highs and lows. itâ€™s equal parts a beautiful sunset as it is a stormy night. no one likes to advertise the tough times, but being able to ride it out through the storm is one of lifeâ€™s many tests. staying grounded during the peaks of joy is equally important, for what comes up must always come down. if thereâ€™s a storm on the horizon, brace yourself but know you donâ€™t have to face all challenges alone. if a tidal wave is approaching, friends and family are the boat that helps you sail through. iâ€™ve had moments where iâ€™ve sat alone and questioned myself and the direction iâ€™m headed. itâ€™s easy to get lost in your thoughts but hard to find the courage to talk to someone in those moments. just know that each storm passes and eventually thereâ€™s a beautiful sunset in your future. if youâ€™re stuck in a storm and want to talk about something youâ€™re struggling with but canâ€™t find someone, shoot me a message. happy to help you find the sunset on your horizon ğŸŒ…

__label__Dublin,Ireland on the road to recovery from a nasty flu these past few days. thanks for all the well wishes via fb and good ol' snapchat!

currently at the dublin central library grinding away at some fun blog posts that have been long overdue, so stay tuned!

also a quick reminder that the world is only as bad and as dangerous as we allow ourselves to believe.

be careful how much of the media's fear-mongering agenda you feed your mind.

of the 7+ billion people on this planet, i'm still putting my hope in the 99% of those with caring hearts and loving spirits that don't get international coverage for the millions of good deeds done around the world everyday.

despite the tragedies everywhere, i'm smiling in the face of hatred and terrorism because it will never win, especially if we refuse to buy into their fear-filled propaganda.

love, light, and hope to you all today. stay inspired, encouraged, and cognizant of what you're feeding your psyche.

p.s. i'll be in london this weekend if anyone is around! and i just might have my voice back by then too. #wishfulthinking

__label__Iceland almost 10 years ago i took on one of my first real editorial (magazine) assignments. timmy turner had almost lost his life fighting a deadly staph infection that had started chewing its way through his head. a routine training swim in huntington beach had led to a bad sinus infection... then a coma... and the last thing he remembers is waking up in intensive care with stitches in his skull. 
a pro surfer & filmmaker that had spent most his life in remote tropical waves in the middle of nowhere had now been told by doctors that he was most likely never going to surf again.... well in warm water at least. so he decided to do the most logical thing & devote himself to only cold water where the risk of staph was almost non existent. he spent the next few years exploring canada, ireland, iceland and more.
.

i knew timmy as a friend shooting in california & all the sudden i found myself sharing a tent snow camping & swimming in frigid water with him & a crew in northern iceland on assignment for mens journal. i had somehow led the photo editor (who's still a good friend) to believe i knew what i was doing. i was completely out of my realm trying to balance shooting a surf trip with portraiture amidst capturing his return to the ocean & filmmaking in an honest way. .

today i still consider myself lucky to have been apart of that story... i learned more lessons that i could have ever imagined from timmy & the whole team. was i was the best person for the job? probably not, but i realized i was willing to sacrifice & give more of myself shooting someone i respected & telling a story i cared about than anything else. @timmyturnerferal

__label__Goa,India for my last full night in goa, the sun again managed to break through the haze, pull the clouds in and present a stunner of a sunset. we were driving the whole time and usually that might make a photographer sad but i felt elated as i hung my head out the window and let the warm breeze whip my hair from my face for an unobstructed view of the fields and towns lit by the setting sun. palm trees became abstract modern art and birds swooped in and out of frame in what seemed like a slow dance. i didn't yet know how bittersweet the next day would be. all i knew at that moment was that i'd somehow managed to finally fall in love with india during #escape2goa ....

__label__Bali,Indonesia mother nature is truly an enigma. one minute you're basking in her glory in the jungle vibes of ubud, the next, your google alerts notifies you that yet another earthquake has shaken up the neighboring island of lombok a few hours ago.

again, in bali we're doing just fine. we feel the aftershocks, but it's nothing worth mentioning when you see a death toll of almost 350.

being so close now, we figured the best way to help would be to pool together our money and fill up a boat with as many supplies as possible to those stranded on the island or unable to evacuate.

you incredible people of the internet have raised over 2 grand in just a day! if anyone else would like to help, you can go to the link in my bio and any donation you leave, please sign your name and/or instagram handle because we'll be taking pictures of all the receipts and sending to people individually so they can know what exactly their money went towards.

so amazed at how quickly everyone has rallied together, especially @mylifesatravelmovie @roxannetaylormedia and @beckyvandijk from @wearetravelgirls.

this moment of stillness i captured with my tripod perfectly encapsulates the monstrosity yet beauty of mother nature. praying for better days for this magical country â¤ğŸ‡®ğŸ‡©

__label__ZionNationalPark while most visitors to zion national park target (and never leave) the main canyon, the upper east canyon (on the eastern side of the park) holds some of the best scenery and hikes. besides the well known formation known as checkerboard mesa, there are a ton of really fascinating formations and hikes to discover on the east side. you can use any of the pullouts and scramble up (or down) some of the coolest slickrock you will ever find. this little gem of a tree springing to life from the sandstone mound is no more than fifty yards from an easy pullover, yet most people cruise on by with eyes only for the main canyon. you never know what wonders are hidden around the bend when you venture a bit off the beaten path. next time you are in zion, be sure to spend some time exploring the endlessly cool formations on the eastern side of the park

__label__Goa,India she was just a baby when she came to goa. her sister and she left behind their rag-picking family in karnataka and came to goa in search of a better life. but rag-picking was the only thing they knew. so for 20 years, they lived off the dumpsters in a small makeshift settlement off mapusa in north goa...
.
.
then 20 years later, goaâ€™s first high tech waste management plant opened up and hired rag pickers from across the state. after all, they were pros at dealing at waste. thatâ€™s where i first saw her, wearing a protective coat, sturdy gloves, face mask, eyes on the moving conveyor belt, picking out recyclables as all kinds of things rolled along - curry covered boxes, plastic in all forms, rotting vegetables, tattered clothes, umbrellas, muck covered toys, even rotting carcasses ğŸ˜²
.
.
later during lunch break, as she ate along with her sister and brother in law, also employees, she seemed nothing but joyful. unlike her rag-picking days, she now has a uniform, a decent salary, health care, her own room in a rented house, public transport to work. after chatting a while about our lives, i shyly asked if i could take a photo of her. of course, she said, and whipped out a shiny samsung camera phone from her pocket to take photos with me! .
.
the tattoo on her arm is her name and her sisterâ€™s, made with sharp hot metal while she was still a kid... and as i chatted with her bubbly self, i promised myself that whenever i decide to stay in one place again, iâ€™ll make sure i segregate my waste. and until then, iâ€™ll try to convince my hosts to do it wherever i go. no human should have to sort through someone elseâ€™s waste all day, even if they do it with gratitude. i also heard from the manager later, that if more people segregated their waste, theyâ€™d be able to recycle and compost so much more. things we seldom think about as we go about our privileged lives ğŸ¤”
.
.
this post is part of my #voicesofruralindia series where i hope to challenge myself to take more portrait photos and share stories of ordinary people i meet on my travels. .
.

__label__SriLanka due to the many years of civil war and its end in 2008, sri lanka is still in tourist beginnings. one can therefore often see and experience the genuine everyday life of the locals. it's best to mix with the hustle and bustle of the weekly markets. fresh vegetables, fruits, fish, spices and many other delicacies are waiting to be discovered. a true intoxication for the senses. wonderful scents, sounds and scrambling and last but not least the many bright colors will fascinate you and bring you closer to the everyday life of the people of sri lanka. the prices are of course also outrageously cheap;) fake branded products such. in thailand, however, you are looking in vain, but you will find a lot of authenticity in a country that will open more and more to tourism.

__label__Iceland this was literally one of the first photos i ever took of the amazing northern lights (aurora borealis). i was woken up in the middle of the night (about 3 am) to a banging on my hotel room door in southeastern iceland that the aurora were dancing in the night sky. it was late september, and although i had hoped to see them, the odds at this time are not great. but within 2 seconds of the words "northern lights" being said i was already gathering my gear. the night was crisp and clear...perfect for aurora. i was in such a rush, and was so friggin exciting, that i completely forgot to bring my tripod. big mistake when shooting at night. i ran outside, climbed a hill, and stared with amazement at the dancing lights above my head. quickly snapping out of it, it was then i realized i had no tripod. ugh! i firmly believe photography is a study in problem solving...the ability to make something out of nothing is often the difference between missing and getting the shot.  i was too nervous to run back to the hotel and possibly miss the show. so i looked around and decided to build a makeshift tripod out of the surrounding rocks. lying on my back, staring at my camera just two feet or so off the ground, using the 2-second shutter release delay, this was the literally one of the first photos. all told, i'd say a job well done. and an amazing first aurora experience i will never forget. have you seen these dancing night lights ?

__label__JoshuaTreeNationalPark half the park is after dark. when most people are sleeping, the stars come out to play. i love astrophotography, not only because i get to see the stars at night but also because i mostly have them all to myself. the quiet, cold night air is intoxicating, as are the stars that glimmer above. the downside is waking up at ungodly hours and crawling out of the warm bed. but i cannot remember a time when i wasn't glad i forced myself up and out of bed, no matter how strong the urge to stay sleeping. fighting inertia is something at which every photographer must be a master. this is a composite startrail image of about 200 separate images, each taken at 30-second exposure around 3 a.m., just after the moon set and before twilight.  this was one of my favorite rock formations at joshua tree and it just so happened to be right by our campsite at jumbo rocks campground

joshua tree national park @joshuatreenps (15 of 59) 
shot with fujifilm x-t1 and xf16-55mm f2.8 lens

__label__DeathValleyNationalPark on a project of this magnitude, itâ€™s necessary to have a plan, but equally (if not more) important to stay flexible. we had a rough route through the npâ€™s that we wanted to take for this project, but the superbloom event in death valley national park is really when we threw that original plan out the door. some of you might remember, but 2016 was an epic year for the desert flower bloom in death valley. heavy winter rainfall in the area led to an incredible (super!) bloom on the valley floor in the spring. it was breathtaking to see the desert have so much life. we were still far away from dvnp when the superbloom started to blow up. it was a no brainer....we had to scrap our plans and get out there asap. it was a major diversion in the trip that would necessitate some serious rerouting. but it was so worth it. plus, we got there on my birthday (march 5)...what a way to spend a birthday! __label__Burano,Veneto,Italy burano island ğŸŒˆ
.

i have never seen the 'instagram effect' on a destination as much as i saw in burano. this tiny island of rainbow painted houses is indeed incredibly photogenic, but it's also a place that people call home. early in the morning when i arrived, it was a sanctuary of calm. women knitted outside their houses, rung out their laundry and men fixed their boats on the canals which replace roads. a few hours later, masses of tourists arrived on ferries, and the locals retreated inside and locked their shutters closed, while daytrippers posed with their laundry lines and patio displays for the perfect shot. .

i am too a tourist and an instagrammer. i shoot often on the streets and local people appear in a great portion of my photographs. the place left me with a big dilemma in my mind, one i'm still trying to figure out. tourism can do wonders for communities, but at the extreme - it can also shatter them and i fear burano may become the next victim. what are your thoughts on this? have you found similar places around the world?

__label__Florence,Italy if you've followed me for a while or checked out my website, you know that i love finding really interactive kid activities, whether it's museum tours or cooking classes or scavenger hunts through medieval fortresses. and i love italy, having spent well over a year of my life there. so i was excited to have lunch this week with the folks from @italiakidsonline / @elaiatravel, at an italian restaurant of course. we talked italy and kid activities for hours. what's cool is that they've already developed amazing-sounding weeklong workshops for kids throughout italy that incorporate art, culture, history, cooking and even video production. they're for ages 6-12 and i'm going to sign up my kids next summer if i can make the dates work. if you're looking for a fun, really unique kids day camp in italy, check them out. and nope, they're not paying me to say this! i just love that they've created these programs, and i wish that there were workshops like this in other cool destinations. this photo? it's a slightly different view of florence, from our boat on the arno going under the ponte santa trinita. our kids loved it. take your kids everywhere! #visitflorence

__label__Bali finally caught up to where i am currently: bali, indonesia.
.
i must confess that i didnâ€™t have very high expectations for bali, precisely because everyone raves about it. i'm not a fan of the stereotypical vacation spots, and avoid tourists traps at all costs.
.
but... bali is special. i resisted it, really i did, but it got to me too. i've been spending most of my time with locals, and i'm in awe of the special energy that envelops this place. it's naturally so gorgeous, yet the people are what get me. they are connected - maybe the best way to describe it is to the earth. they are grounded, and seem to have nurtured a deep understanding and appreciation for the slow art of living.
.
coming up this week will be stories of my time in bali, focusing on the people that i've met and how they've contributed to helping me understand why it's so crucial to cultivate balance and calm in my life. .
.
this photo was taken in a super empty beach that my new local friends took me to. jumping for joy as a token of gratitude for @theglobejumpers, who recently featured me on their amazing account and also have provided me with so much support throughout this journey! thanks guys! will always #keepjumping <3 .

__label__NewYork,NewYork long time insta fam ğŸ‘‹ğŸ» the past couple of weeks i have been enveloped in my own overthinking and the what ifâ€™s and what could have beenâ€™s. you know, alternate universe with other outcomes than what is present. it has taken a toll on me emotionally and mentally. dear friends have been very patient with me listening to me and waiting for me to process it all. for them, iâ€™m grateful.
.
.
during times like this, i like to go over pictures as they are vivid reminders of certain memories. this was my first time visiting nyc. it was thrilling and i was upset because of certain situations that didnâ€™t line up. i focused on why not instead of enjoying the moment and the place i visited. i looked around and the streets were buzzing with people from all walks of life. there were lines for broadway shows and lots of big screens and digital signage everywhere. living in the moment is easy said than done. but here is to practicing it everyday and here is to owning our doubts. here is to a better present for a better tomorrow. to more first timesâœŒğŸ¼

__label__Jaipur,Rajasthan this photo might represent the scenario for every twenty-something out there with a multitude of options and passions, but only two feet to work with.

perhaps in another life, on the 7th day, god would've siesta'd, but still had time to create us with 6 arms and legs to keep up with our 72-tab browser mindset.

i admire those who got to 80 years old and tried their hand at 3 different careers, fulfilling 3 different areas of their lives.

i don't think we're meant to do the same thing every day for the next 60 years, call it a life, and die.

we're all so talented and too dynamic to have just a single story written about our lives.

stepping out on faith is scary. but what's scarier is the amount of people that take their dreams to the grave with them.

because they sat around waiting on their parents' approval. on the perfect amount of savings. on their partner's situation to get better.

there's nothing selfish about pursuing a life that makes you wildly excited about monday mornings.

anybody who tries to tell you otherwise isn't the kind of energy you should be surrounding yourself with.

it's time to stop seeking approval from those with entrepreneurial minds but an elementary work ethic.

i've said it before and i'll say it again. our dreams are all different, but our need for fulfillment is the same.

when was the last time you did something that truly made you feel worthy?

worthiness isn't birthed overnight. and self-confidence might be the longest and most unstable road in the world. but anything worth having in life requires working towards it daily.

financial stability. a happy marriage. a healthy heart and body.

so maybe you're stuck in the middle of a crossroad but you're on the verge of turning your whys into why nots.

the universe always conspires in your favor when your work ethic meets it halfway.

here's to my fellow dreamers. may you forever continue to be anything but normal ğŸ¤˜ğŸ¾ photo credit | @dakotaadan

__label__Havana,Cuba because @dante.vincent and i decided to visit cuba by the most legal means open to americans when we booked our trip 6 months ago, we chose a sanctioned photography tour with @harryfisch.correo. harry encouraged us to be bold in getting to know cuban people, to approach them and ask them for photos. at first, i felt timid despite my decades of experience behind the camera but as our hours & days in havana wore on, i realized moments like this were my very favorite. even better than the colorful cars and the crumbling architecture, that i'd so looked forward to before arriving -- was the sense that we were connecting with what *actually* makes cuba special. it's the people. so passionate, so quick to smile at you, so curious to know your story & to share their own, so open to sharing what precious little they have so that you leave wanting only to return again. and soon! sure enough, that's what dantÃ© and i want to do: return. this handsome local smiled at me, inviting me to take his photo while we were walking in a very local section of older havana and though he had to continue working instead of sharing his story, his is only one of perhaps two dozen or more faces that i could share with you! #facesofcuba
also, this week on the @circa39miami & @palmshotelmiami feeds i'm sharing photos of the experience dantÃ© & i are having here in florida  before we finally return home to nyc. get your dose of palm trees and ocean views there since that's not something we found in cuba ğŸ˜‰ğŸŒ´

__label__Antarctica at first glance, this doesnâ€™t look like such an uncommon photo, right? just some birds circling over an iceberg in antarctica. but like most things in antarctica, thereâ€™s much more below the surface. these birds are really special and beautiful birds called snow petrals, found almost exclusively in the icy realm of the white continent. they are petite birds with snow white feathers, coal black eyes and beak, and bluish grey feet. they tend to flutter about more than fly. to see one up close is a real treat, as they are stunningly beautiful, resembling little angels in a way. but in many trips to antarctica iâ€™ve never seen so many in one place at one time. this sighting is quite rare, as far as i can tell. the lack of color coupled with the ice and large flock of one of my favorite birds in the world took my breath away. it was a beautiful sight that turned out to be one of my favorite sightings on recent expeditions. to know that these birds congregate like this, and are probably doing this exact thing right now, makes me smile. antarctica is magical.

__label__Stockholm,Sweden do you want to change, but don't know where to begin? in my coaching work, i've noticed that people who reach out to me want to make a change in their lives... but feel completely stuck on how to get there.
â €â €â € â €
change (or lack thereof) starts with our beliefs. we each have a set of beliefs, and they sometimes limit us. for example: you believe you are not good enough. you believe that life is unfair. you believe people are not trustworthy. and so on.
â €â €â € â €
when we rigidly subscribe to our beliefs, everything we experience will affirm or deny those beliefs. your world becomes a place where you are not good enough, life is unfair, and people are not trustworthy.
â €â €â € â €
it doesn't have to be that way.
â €â €â € â €
change begins when we choose to let our beliefs go and see the world for what it is.
â €â €â € â €
letting go of your beliefs does not mean you don't have them. it just means you are not enslaved by them.
â €â €â € â €
when we recognize that our beliefs are subjective and a result of our experience, we can then choose who we want to be. we make choices based on the present moment rather than the conditioning of our past.
â €â €â € â €
it all depends on what's more important to you - changing your life, or sticking to your beliefs regardless of how they limit you?
â €â €â € â €

__label__TourEiffel ever since i started travel writing five years ago i've wanted to do a post on what it costs for a family to go to disneyland, and then show where else in the world they could go for the same money. there's nothing wrong with disneyland per se, but the world is amazing, and kids gain so much from being exposed to it! 
my post went live last night and already has thousands of views and a lot of great comments. i love hearing that so many people have gone to disneyland and disney world and thought the same thing - where else could all of these families go for this much money? the post's at babbo.com/disneyland and is linked from my profile. let me know your thoughts too. disneyland or the world? or both? 
and yes, one of my suggestions is paris - pictured. you could head over from virtually anywhere in the us in june and spend six nights and still spend less than you would at disneyland.

__label__NewYork,NewYork this is leticia (@ticiaripa). her dream is to incorporate her passion of travel and helping people into her career and journey in life. she also happens to be my best friend.

whenever she comes over, we have a routine that extends as far back as our 13 years of friendship; she watches me meander from drawer to drawer, looking for the perfect outfit to wear to our next adventure. frozen with indecision, i ask her which outfit i should select before even trying it on. her answer is the same, every time: â€œjust try it.â€

by repeating that simple mantra over the years, leticia taught me a lesson that extends far beyond outfits: it is far better to try something we are curious about and be unafraid to change if it doesnâ€™t fit, than to remain stagnantly suspended in indecision. 

let go of the irrational fear that something will go wrong before even knowing what itâ€™ll look like. have faith that your intuition is guiding you in the right direction. just try it. #thenomadsoasisproject #celinnesoasis #followyourdream

p.s. for those of you wondering, the outfits turn out fabulous ğŸ˜›

__label__CapeTown,WesternCape creative constipation ğŸ’©
â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢â€¢
iâ€™ve admittedly been a bit disconnected mentally and physically from ig for the past few weeks. like clockwork, this â€œconstipationâ€ kicks in every year towards year end. i physically canâ€™t bring myself to pick up a camera, let alone pose for one. i feel like i have nothing interesting to say and simply donâ€™t have the energy to create or share.â€¨â€¢â€¨i started to realize that mayyybe sharing 5 blog posts weekly, daily ig stories, weekly youtube videos, daily ig posts, and daily twitter, facebook and pinterest posts would reduce my normally overflowing jar of creativity to crumbs. (guess thatâ€™s not all that surprising, is it?)
â€¢
when i come home between trips, i nurture my mental and physical health by slowing down, developing a routine, and binge watching mindless tv. i have to balance my highly-overstimulating lifestyle with simple pleasures.â€¨â€¢â€¨just like my mental and physical health, iâ€™ve found that i also need to nurture my creativity. when iâ€™m feeling creatorâ€™s block, i distance myself from my normal routine. i stop posting. i stop sharing. i stop shooting. i start reading. i start baking. i learn a new skill. i seek anything creative that is totally unrelated to what i â€˜normallyâ€™ do. (i even started a â€œhome sweet africaâ€ cross-stitch set lol!)
â€¢
einstein called this act â€œcombinatory playâ€ â€” opening one mental channel by dabbling in another. when creativity is your job, the stakes are high. you canâ€™t always be creative just for the fun of it. you have to post daily, â€˜beat the algorithmâ€™ and deliver â€˜epicâ€™ content constantly. by exploring new creative outlets, it keeps my inspiration in motion, but relieves me of the pressure i put on myself. i spend my time trying things that are ok for me to not be good at, and i start to slowly refill my creative jar.â€¨â€¢â€¨in true â€œinstagram inspirationâ€ form, i shared this nugget of self-awareness on a pretty picture thatâ€™s completely unrelated to the message. but, i hope that because of it, some of you relate to it and seek out that soul nourishing creative break you also need.â€¨â€¢â€¨more pretty pictures soon! promise

__label__Budapest,Hungary the sun rises and sets on both good and evil. which makes each new day a blessing, as our tomorrows are never guaranteed.

i pray we as a whole continue to cultivate and focus on the good, the pure, and the magic in this world.

especially during times we allow the bad to cloud our judgment and let us think our good hearts are the minority.

my heart goes out to everyone in nice today, and it was such a relief to see my friends there, one by one, mark themselves as safe on facebook.

we also had a @busabouteurope crew there yesterday who've thankfully all been accounted for.

love and light to everyone today.

we also say goodbye to budapest and hello to croatia for the ultra music festival this weekend.

thankful for continued journey mercies throughout my travels and i long for the day we can wake up without a new hashtagged city or person to mourn over ğŸ’”

__label__Bangalore,India looking out.

it is often a dilemma i've found myself in: to find a perfect picture, to decide whether to post a picture or not, to decide the worth of a photograph or a bunch of words to the likes of the audience.

rare a realisation that you never really understand what the artist tries to convey over a their art - we are all bound by our vision of the world. all you can is relate.

and i've probably figured out that you cannot let the mess you are made up of conform to the moulds offered by the world.

there's nothing quite striking about this picture, nor do we have plato lending a quote for the caption; all we do is an overprocessed picture filling out a random feed.

here's to being the unique kind of weird you are. here's to finding beauty in everything and not meaning.

i can't believe it's been almost 4 years ago since i sat here looking out over ko phi phi in thailand. this was my first ever solo trip. i remember sitting anxiously in the airport in melbourne as i awaited my flight to thailand.

a million emotions ran over me as i questioned every aspect of my decision to travel southeast asia on my own. "would i be safe?" "what if nobody spoke english?" "what if i was lonely?" i sat here, a week after arriving in thailand, feeling all of the scared and worrisome emotions wash away with the tide. i knew my life would never be the same and committed to sharing my own story in hopes that it would inspire others to take the same leap of faith in life.

and so began the journey of the blonde abroadâ€¦

__label__Paris,France i was in paris yesterday to kick off a project my team was doing with another team in our paris office.
.
i remember being so anxious the first few times i had to run workshops like this. always worried about conflicts. or the possibility of the day being unproductive. or just generally a waste of everybodyâ€™s time. so far none of the workshops ive done have turned into a complete disaster although some couldâ€™ve gone better. now i still get nervous but just for the first 5 minutes then i morph into a workshop fiend.
.
it helped that i learned from every previous workshops iâ€™ve done. i iterate on my workshop tool kit every chance i get. i copied things that i liked from other people. with pride. i dropped things that i tried that didnt work. with no remorse. iâ€™ve learned to assume good intent (a phrase iâ€™ve been hearing a lot lately) even when things werent exactly going as planned. and i listened to feedback given to me by managers and peers who had the unfortunate luck of having to be in my workshop. in the end itâ€™s like developing new products. test. learn. iterate. what a nerd. but i love it now
.
the thing is my introvert self goes absolutely bonkers after every workshop i do. keeping the room focused and engaged to ensure a conclusion in the end is not easy for people like me who get drained from people-ing. at the end of the day, i spend what little energy i have left trying not to lock myself in the bathroom to be alone until i can stand the thought of having conversations again. welp. ğŸ˜…
.
bonus: it doesnâ€™t hurt that doing workshops in our paris office means getting treated to this view everytime we take a break. i always get the urge to break out into the entire les miserables song list whenever i am here. someday. one day.

__label__HoChiMinhCity,Vietnam no trunk, no problem. can you spot the 12 bags of rice/potato/magic that he's perfectly stacked on his motorbike? #lawdhammercy

just another everyday intersection where the streets of chaos and freedom collide.

motorbikes, cars, and people will be coming at you from every direction. so if you need to cross a street, only look straight ahead and just go for it.

if you stop or wait for someone to pass, you ironically mess up the flow of traffic. motorbikes are timing your movement ahead of time, so stopping only throws them off.

it takes a bit to get confident in this, but once you see how majestically they swerve and dodge pedestrians, you'll realize this is how they were taught to drive. and they're damn good at it!

vietnam is a country where everything just goes, and there's a beauty in this type of systematic chaos because somehow it's actually quite sustainable.

#busabout #busaboutvietnam #hochiminhcity #saigon #seasia

__label__HongKong what does freedom mean to you?

for some people it's a feeling, for others, it's a physical state of being.

i often jokingly talk about my very strict and sheltered nigerian upbringing, where i wasn't allowed to watch pg movies until i was 18, relationships were something you weren't allowed to have until you were married ğŸ¤”, and how you will very much fear the iron backhand of your mother well into your 50's.

but my definition of freedom is as literal as it gets, because i never got a taste of that in my youth, so i crave it every day now.

and it's probably why i get such itchy feet and love to constantly be on the move.

freedom exists on a spectrum though, rather than a form of an absolute.

breaking free from archaic and soul-crushing ideas of what success means in nigerian culture, is the current race i'm running now.

despite the tiresome trek, i recognize that this is freedom.

__label__Bangkok,Thailand #tbt - i want to do a better job of sharing everyday life when i travel, in addition to those amazing landscapes and architectural marvels that are so famous. i thought iâ€™d start with a photo i took at a night market on my most recent trip to thailand; one that shows why i love the city so very much. we all love different cities for different reasons and none of us have the same travel experience. i have a short list of cities i could return to a thousand times and never be bored and bangkok is near the top of that list. i honestly probably shouldnâ€™t like bangkok as much as i do. my first trip there many years ago was also my first time visiting a so-called developing country. i still vividly remember walking out of the airport and being inundated byâ€¦everything. the smells, the wet air and the cacophony of people was all a lot to take. later during that same trip i was swindled by a fake tourist-cop, not the first time someone has been cheated in bangkok, but i was deeply shaken. i walked back to my hotel rom that evening in tears and vowed never to return. thankfully, that feeling was fleeting and within a day or so i was back out enjoying lunch at streets stalls and visiting temples and palaces. since then iâ€™ve returned many times and as i said, today itâ€™s a favorite place to spend some time. not to do or see any one thing, but just to be there, to enjoy the city for its intrinsic value. sometimes, thatâ€™s enough.

__label__YosemiteNationalPark continuing on with our #california national park exploration, next up is the iconic yosemite national park. i've photographed this park before and have always held a special place in my heart for it. yosemite is simply incredible. it's hard to imagine a more perfect natural setting for a park. my deep feeling for it also puts a burden on photographing it well...doing it the justice it deserves in the limited time we have in each park. but i am happy with the the images, stories, and experiences we had there and am excited to share some of them. let's start with a doozy.....the infamous taft point lookout. there never seems to be a shortage of people willing to risk life and limb for an epic photograph. luckily, i was there at the right time to capture it.

__label__Mexico ever since i started travel blogging over 7 years ago, there's a question that repeatedly pops up in my inbox. it is some version of this: "how do i convince my parents to let me travel?"
.
.
i know there was a time when travel was considered a luxury, an escape from everyday life; it was expensive, borders were closed, visas were difficult. but times have changed and how!
.
.
in this world that seems to be fearful of "foreigners", where all that we read about in the media breeds fear and hatred, it is more important now than ever to travel. because a school textbook can't describe the heartwarming hospitality of a traditional muslim family in jordan, or the proud and light-hearted spirit of ethiopians, or the egalitarian way of life in central america. fancy degrees might sound good to your friends, but real learning happens when you're stranded in a country you know nothing about, not even the language, and a kind stranger goes far out of his way to help you. even death - or the fear of it - acquires new perspective on the road.
.
.
no, travel is not a break from life. it is education in its truest, purest form. we need now, more than ever, for people to travel out of their comfort zones, to discover life beyond the cities and cubicles, to open up their world, to chase their dreams. we need less bankers and engineers, and more artists, musicians, writers, travellers, entrepreneurs, sportspeople, dreamers.
.
.
the above is an excerpt from an â€œopen letter to indian parentsâ€ i wrote a while ago, on my blog. the full version is in my profile ğŸ˜‰
.
.
and you, have you had battles at home to let you travel / travel solo? .
.

it is really inhuman. i only had my eternal lioness smile as an answer towards this. on the other hand, the last day i learned that almost no one knows that it is for example forbidden for a unicorn to drive a car in russia. so i can only ask you to start supporting unicorns who are going through this every single day. they really deserve all your love! ğŸ’–ğŸ’–ğŸ’–ğŸŒˆğŸŒˆğŸŒˆ

__label__Delhi,India perspective will take you further in life than any plane ticket ever will. this story will frustrate some of you, but i need to share it, because itâ€™s a regular part of my travels.

india is a country of 1.3 billion people, and whenever i interact with locals, i always bear in mind that our exchange isnâ€™t simply between two people.

iâ€™m representing the entire black community, and since many indians have never met black people in person before, i anticipated some hesitation scattered between the smiles of adoration and selfies.

i walked to the elevator at my hotel in delhi and just a couple steps behind me was a family of 4. a mother, two teenaged sons, and a daughter.

the elevator arrived and i entered first and held my arm out - the universal gesture of â€œplease enter." but the mother just stared. the sons awkwardly turned their backs. and the daughter, about 8 or 9 years old, made a small step forward that was met with a push back by her motherâ€™s hand.

i did the indian head waggle (lol, my way of signaling that i come in peace) and motioned for them to come in.

the daughter again walked forward while the mother hesitantly followed, and eventually so did the two sons.

about a decade later, we arrived at the ground floor and i signaled with my arm for them to be let out first. tense, no one except the daughter made eye contact.

but don't blame india, this happens to me everywhere. on a packed bus when there is one seat left next to me, but people rather stand. or at the airport waiting rooms when i sit down and someone will get up and move away.

this is the life i chose. to expose myself to the realities of how black people are viewed globally. and to actively do the work of not only being a great representation of americans, but of black people altogether.

so i can no longer get upset by these interactions, because i donâ€™t know what movie or rumor that mother heard about black people that made her feel like a two-story elevator ride with one wasnâ€™t a risk she wanted to take.

itâ€™s a humbling reminder as black people that we can smile, be friendly, and even speak a few words of the local language, yet still be subjected to the pigment of our skin. ğŸ’›

__label__Morocco sabah el kheir, morocco! this is my second time in this magnetic country and it's just as sensational and intoxicating as i remember it back in 2014.

morocco is a country of hustle and bustle, and though i came here solo last time, it's been so handy having a crew with me this time around.

moroccans are genuine and warm people, but if you can speak one of their languages (arabic or french), you'll get to experience the full extent of that warmth.

i "yala'd" and "habibi'd" my way through the medina, exchanging smiles, banter, and the all-too-familiar greetings of "mama africa!" and other unifying diaspora dialogue that always makes me smile.

marrakesh continues to be one of my favorite cities in the world because i live for its madness, chaos, and intensity.

one minute there's a donkey charging your way, the next a man is trying to hustle you wray pans (african ray bans ğŸ˜…), all while you're dodging a couple hundred motorbikes a minute and resisting the temptation and beautiful assault of the spices and foods all around you.

charm, culture, and cuisine in one spot. marrakesh is life.

and it's countries like morocco that make me fall back in love with traveling, nomadic life, and getting to taste, breathe, and dance with some of the most enchanting cultures of the world.

burj khalifa (arabic: Ø¨Ø±Ø¬ Ø®Ù„ÙŠÙØ©â€, "khalifa tower"), known as burj dubai prior to its inauguration, is a skyscraper in dubai, united arab emirates, and is the tallest man-made structure in the world, at 829.8 m (2,722 ft). construction began on 21 september 2004, with the exterior of the structure completed on 1 october 2009. the building officially opened on 4 january 2010,and is part of the new 2 km2 (490-acre) development called downtown dubai at the 'first interchange' along sheikh zayed road, near dubai's main business district. the tower's architecture and engineering were performed by skidmore, owings and merrill of chicago, with adrian smith as chief architect, and bill baker as chief structural engineer. the primary contractor was samsung c&t of south korea.

__label__Istanbul,Turkey coming to @ambientefair this friday, our bassa lamp is inspired by one of the 23 consonants of the â€˜bassa vahâ€™ alphabet.
.
.
bassa is a language still spoken today in parts of liberia and sierra leone but its alphabet fell out of use after being labeled a â€œfailed scriptâ€, despite the formation of an association in 1959 for its promotion.
.
.
the name originates from the bassa word 'vah', meaning 'to throw a sign'. it is widely believed that the script developed from an earlier bassa communication system of signs made from chewed leaves which would then be carved into trees and left in set locations where they would be found and interpreted. as this system developed, it was employed to avoid slave traders and was therefore suppressed by colonial powers.
.
.

__label__Bali,Indonesia i heard something recently that stuck with me: you canâ€™t compare your inside to someone elseâ€™s outside. on this platform as with most social media, iâ€™m sure it looks like thereâ€™s a lot of perfection in the lives of so many women who travel online, bolstered by strength and bravery that is somehow out of reach. but the truth is we all struggle, self-judge, and have our demons. itâ€™s scary to share my inside, but i also think itâ€™s important to be honest and raw, so with a deep breath, here it is: today marks one year since the last time i drank alcohol. i used to struggle with it while i traveled, while i climbed mountains, while i built my own business from nothing. it was there, a thorn in my side that i couldnâ€™t remove until last july. iâ€™m far from perfect, i really felt like the opposite for so long. since then life got better, i got stronger, my work became more meaningful and more of you came to be part of it and support me without even realizing thatâ€™s what you were doing. thank you for being here. thank you for being such a big inspiration to me. thank you for every uplifting comment and message. you mean so much to me.

i wrote a post about how i transitioned and what changed in my life since i did. i hope that if itâ€™s what you need to read today, that it reaches you somehow. cheers to strength, humility, and gratitude ğŸ™ and to another year with a new lease on life.

__label__Venice,Italy i just want to take a moment to thank you guys for the love and support from my latest blog post.

as i said, the words were harsh, but necessary. it resonated with most, and struck a nerve with others, and that's completely okay.

took a couple days to catch up, but the amount of emails from people opening up their homes to me around africa brought me to tears.

that, and other travelers sharing their stories of also feeling disconnected from their home towns after opening up their mind to the lessons of the world.

it's a hard place to be. loving and cherishing the people from your past, but knowing there's limited space/patience for them in your future.

it doesn't mean you need to cut people out of your life. you can continue to support and wish them well from afar.

what you do need to do though, is foster new relationships that grow, challenge, and develop the person you're meant to be.

stagnancy is regression in my book. and if i'm not learning something new every day, i'm wasting precious time.

i've always said people aren't inspired by perfection, they're inspired by transparency.

so i will continue to share the raw, the real, and the gritty of my heart, because that's the only way i know how to write.

again, my platform isn't here to coddle your privilege or comfort your ego.

it is so nice to be in a mental space where you feel so confident about the direction of your life. 
this will excite most and intimidate others. luckily, the only approval i need is mine and the man upstairs.

here's to new beginnings and those open to growing with me | link in bio for those who'd like to read the blog post in question â¤

__label__Paris,France the other day instagram sent me a survey with questions such as whether instagram is good for the world ğŸ™„
â€¢
thereâ€™s a lot of criticism of influencers here promoting materialistic lifestyles by showing off expensive hotels, constant unboxing, or rooms so full of shoes that you could probably dress an entire village in them.
â€¢
however, this trend and people being interested in seeing it isnâ€™t just a side effect of instagram. â€¢
if you go to the louvre (since this photo is from paris) and see paintings from letâ€™s say for instance baroque era, a lot of them are either portraits of rich people, still life of fancy objects or food, or genre scenes from events. because there was a demand for it. â€¢
how many painters showed off peasants or servants? very few. and those who did focus on authenticity like for instance my favorite vermeer died poor and in huge debt. â€¢
i donâ€™t think we, as humans, changed that much - we have curiosity in things most of us canâ€™t have, such as expensive stuff. â€¢
we just need to remember that the art/creations we see here in photos arenâ€™t always peopleâ€™s real lives - clothes can be rented, getting to the perfect spot can take forever, and some bloggers staying in luxury hotels might actually be lonely and broke. â€¢ 
for example, today i spent the day on a couch in my pajamas eating haribo gummy bears (turns out theyâ€™re great for clearing a blocked nose, lol!). ğŸ˜‰

__label__ZionNationalPark i often find myself living in the future. looking to the next bend, and assuming that happiness must be right up there. maybe if i run a little faster i can catch it. 
it's a dangerous thing, chasing happiness. because you can only find it in the present moment. no matter where you are. no matter how much money you have. happiness is always an internal choice.

__label__Dubai,UnitedArabEmirates falcon selfie - only in dubai #helloworldrelay @mydubai @helloworldau

edit: more on this soon, but falconry is one of the middle east's greatest traditions. these birds are idolized here and treated like kings. they even have their own passports. jazzy here was rescued and was released into the wild several times but always returned to @almaha_resort i've held many birds of prey over the years and they are usually hooded like this when they are around people they aren't used to so they don't get agitated. it's normal and not considered to be inhumane at all. i feel so honored i got to hold here and see these amazing creatures in action.

__label__Australia do you have any tattoos?
____________________________________
i get asked by you guys for my tattoos a lot, and despite not being a person that enjoys sharing them or their meaning, i feel like i owe it to you after so many q&as ignoring the subject:

1. three tibetan words on my upper right back. my first tattoo! got it when i was 23.
2. â€œhappiness is only real when sharedâ€ in sinhalese on my left dorsal.
3. number 27 on my upper right triceps. my bday, which ive celebrated 70% of the last decade abroad.
4. r, viking rune. means â€œjourneyâ€ and is also and r, for my last name.
5. eternal lotus. got it in bhutan and represents eternal love. do you remember my stories from that day?
6. captainâ€™s insignia on my left shoulder. got it in bali last month. represents my favorite poem: â€œi am the master of my fate, i am the captain of my soulâ€.
7. kâ€™aaxil: means wild in mayan. did it together with my friends in mexico. the artist messed it up and iâ€™ll probably cover it next month in polynesia.
____________________________________
how about you? what tattoos do you have and what do they mean?

__label__Santorini for those who started following me in the middle of my journey or even recently, and you're wondering how i fell into this crazy lifestyle, i finally come clean - i have a sugar daddy!

hahaha, jk. we can't all be so lucky in life (jk again ğŸ˜‚). but i was just featured on a podcast that recaps my last 4 years, all the way from when i took my first international trip which opened my eyes to a world where i honestly didn't think "my kind" could fit in (listen to understand what i mean by that). 30 countries later, i fought to figure out the balance between what pays my bills and what fuels my passions.

i always say to hustle until your passion becomes your paycheck and words can't describe the feeling of finally achieving that. the world has become my black-sanded beach (photo: perissa beach on santorini island). i hope this inspires someone and thank you, @tranekaenespana for having me!

__label__HongKong this week iâ€™ve spent a lot of time making travel plans for the year, trying to decide where i want to go and when. a place iâ€™m likely to return to (for the third year in a row) is one that has slowly endeared itself to me - hong kong.

when i think of the word frenetic, hong kong usually is the first image that pops into my head. itâ€™s a curious place, intensely modern with skyscrapers, technology and a bustling population that never seems to stop. but itâ€™s not all modernity and flashing lights, thereâ€™s still a traditional side of hong kong to be found and luckily itâ€™s not hidden or tucked away as in some cities. no, hong kong fuses modern life with tradition in a way thatâ€™s rare but somehow makes perfect sense when you visit. sure, you can visit the genius bar in the massive apple store, but then you can grab a meal on the go at any of the gazillion street vendors around town, making classic meals in the same way itâ€™s been done for decades. maybe thatâ€™s what i like best about the city, itâ€™s ability to constantly move forward without losing sight of the values and traditions at the root of its culture.

hong kong has had a very strange history and around town itâ€™s reflected in every way imaginable. for generations the city has been a global crossroads, which it remains today. youâ€™ll hear every language imaginable and people from every corner of the world, all coexisting and all becoming part of the cityâ€™s pulsating matrix. itâ€™s an addictive city, one that begs you to go back for more and i canâ€™t wait to do just that in a few months, to stuff my face silly with all of the amazing food but also to pick up a few more stories from a city that has millions to tell.

__label__Stockholm,Sweden the way i judge a city's progressiveness is through their elderly population and i was pleasantly surprised to learn that the most talkative of the swedish bunch, lies in the older demographic.

i was getting some groceries at the store and a woman came up to me and said how pretty my dress was, and how it made her smile.

a feeble man welcomed me on the metro and shared a couple of his favorite restaurants.

also, whenever they approach me, they always speak in swedish, which i actually appreciate because it's a sign that they're aware and accepting that someone of my ethnic background could have been born and raised here.

again, stockholm is incredibly diverse. way more diverse than other big cities like barcelona, athens, or dublin.

i keep finding myself in awkward situations (like yesterday) but i'm learning how to just mind my business ğŸ˜… #sohard

a taxi pulled off with a woman passenger and her suitcase in the trunk, except he forgot to close the trunk.

i waved my hands and hollered for him to stop, but he didn't see me. the rest of stockholm did, though. and like yesterday's situation, they saw the situation but didn't feel the need to say anything.

the bystander effect (google this, very relevant) is prominent, and while it's not how i'm used to living, it was a culture shock to try and adapt it for a few days to blend in with everyone else.

but man, once they get some alcohol in them, they're like an open book.

sweden is part of what they call the "vodka belt" along with the other nordic and baltic countries, and of course russia.

public drinking, unlike copenhagen, is forbidden, so i made sure my flask wasn't in plain view ğŸ˜Œ

alcohol over 3.5% can only be purchased at licensed restaurants and bars, not at liquor stores like in most countries.

over a century ago, they even had to carry around a book that tracked their alcoholic consumption per month. such interesting laws that obviously died over time but may be telling of their drinking culture today.

stockholm, overall, was a nice change of pace, but now i'm ready for the norwegian beauty up north!

let the good times with @eurail continue!
