__label__GrandCanyonNationalPark the grand canyon is so many things to so many people. at the rim, it's a madhouse of people, busses, activity.....and, of course, some of the most amazing views of any national park in the world. but get down below the rim, into the canyon, and it's as if you stumbled upon a peaceful secret. the crowds thin, the only noise you hear are birds and the mighty rushing colorado river (which formed this canyon), and this magical light that makes everything seem like a fantasyland shines so bright. what a joy to have experienced the infamous rim to rim hike in the grand canyon. my muscles ached, but my heart soared like the condors who call this amazing place home

__label__Utah i wanted to share this months ago, but the experience hadnâ€™t fully set in for me yet. flying through a storm cell in an open cockpit plane ranks pretty high on my list of the most uncomfortable experiences of 2017, but also the most beautiful ... truly. the desert was dappled in sunlight as heavy clouds sent down rain, we could even smell the petrichor rise up as the rain fell on dry soil. .

but in an instant all that beauty kinda faded away as i tucked my camera in my jacket when we realized there was no avoiding this storm. it had encircled us. the cockpit of the small trike started to shake as i could feel tiny drops of rain hit my helmet.. joyful for a second until the heavy rain started to hit. it felt like small nails hitting every part of my exposed skin. hands got shoved in my jacket and head went down as wind & rain overtook us for a brief moment.
.

it felt like a car accident waiting to happen. upon exiting we realized that we were too close & would have to elevate to avoid the others... so still damp we took the aircraft to 12k+ feet & i basically started to freeze. completely unprepared for this 40 minute flight (turned multiple hours)  from monument valley to hanksville i was shivering barely in control. .

there is no room to shake your feet or legs in the cockpit without exposing them to wind, rain or freezing temps. we made a quick descent over the mtns & went back into sunshine where the black asphalt runway provided ample temps to bring my feet & hands back to life. i love when an experience has the ability to simmer a bit. often for me it takes writing it down & thinking on it a bit. thanks @shotsfromabove for keeping us safe on this one.

__label__India my year 2018 , thank you guys for giving this overwhelming response.
in less then 24 hours 1000 comments are there on this video, i want to thank you for this love .
now behind the making :
this video took me 15 days to complete the edit, 
first of all i went to manali shot the video came back, with story telling footage about the year.
but i felt like i want to make this video with a different approach.
i sat down started looking for music then i recalled the time, when i had watched watch tower of turkey, when first time i saw that, i was like dude this is above my imagination, i want to do something like that one day, and i forgot this.
and when again i saw this , i realized yes why not now, i have shot so many footage of 2018 , i have been to mountains, beaches, desserts, hill stations in short i have travelled a lot.
why not to make this happen now.
took whole day to say yes to myself for the idea .
and from then in 15 days, i was editing almost everyday, i used to edit till 5-6 am in the morning without sleeping in night then i used to sleep in day so that in night i have that peace to imagine and create.
.
.

after 8-9 days i reached at edit of 2 minutes 
but i was not happy i deleted whole sequence and restarted with new approach
.
.
trust me there was a time when my friends, family, subsribers everyone was just asking me "how much more time you need" ?
and my answer used to be " i don't know "

800gb data, hundreds of footage , 
content  from over indian destinations 
and one 4 minutes video.
finally yesterday got over with edits and gave you bruh, to post 1000 comments on video.
i thought it will take 6-7 days meanwhile i will start editing new masterpiece from maldives but what ???
one day , just one day and it's done.
i'm so convinced that quality matters in content cause it impacts.
thanks bruh, for love and support.
tommorow trailer will be up on youtube .

__label__NewYork,NewYork a few weeks ago, i posted some ig stories of me getting a tattoo, but i didnâ€™t show you what it was ğŸ˜‰. well, here it is! this lovely piece of ink actually means the world to me (lol, see what i did there), and i wanted to explain why to those who are interested:
â €â €â € â €
one of my favorite quotes of all-time is from the book cloud atlas and it goes, â€œmy life amounts to no more than one drop in a limitless ocean. yet what is any ocean, but a multitude of drops?â€
â €â €â € â €
these words beautifully represent a life paradox that i subscribe to: we are nothing and everything at the same time. itâ€™s hard to accept, but it's quite possible that every action that we take in our lifetime will be forgotten. in the grand scheme of things, our minuscule existence represents little more than a drop in the ocean.
â €â €â € â €
even soâ€¦ our actions do have consequences. every action we take has a ripple effect somewhere in the world. we canâ€™t possibly predict who our actions will impact or inspire, but rest assured that someone out there will be affected by your decisions.
â €â €â € â €
the real question is - what do you want to make of this life? do you want to live it solely for yourself, or do you also want to contribute to the well-being of the planet during your short time here?
â €â €â € â €
collectively, everything we do matters, but only if we are each chipping in our part to contribute to the whole of humanity. together, we are as powerful as the ocean.
â €â €â € â €
this tattoo represents two ends of the spectrum: i want to honor my responsibility in this world, while staying humble to my insignificance. would love to hear your thoughts on this below ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼.

__label__HoChiMinhCity,Vietnam the joy you get from visiting a country so foreign yet so familiar is unparalleled.

i navigate the beautifully chaotic roads "xin chÃ o'ing" my way between a million and one motorbikes, locals, and people that fill the streets of the vibrant ho chi minh city.

i lived here for a month in 2015 and i'm remembering why it was so hard to leave.

vietnamese people and their culture are so colorfully intoxicating, and i'm having fun speaking their language with all the varied syllabic intonations.

during our gala dinner at @ite.hcmc, we swooned over the cultural performances that graced the stage with such precision and perfection, you couldn't program a machine to do it any better.

stuffing my face in vietnamese cuisine has also been a long overdue treat, for i came with all the elastic dresses in the world to accommodate my inevitably expanding waistline.

regrets still mia.

tune into my ig stories to follow all the behind the scenes action, and a huge thanks to @themystdongkhoi for hosting us in their dope space and all of our wonderful sponsors for this event!

__label__MoraineLake moraine lake, my happy place.
but, when i visited last week at sunrise there was no fewer than 200 people there. i was frustrated. any other sunrise i'd been before there was no more than 2 or 3. 
i posted my frustration in a youtube video, and kind of got hit with some backlash. i kind of think it was justified. 
with so many incredible places to see and photograph in alberta, there's no excuse for whining about an excess of people in the classic locations. it just means we have to dig deeper, explore farther, and step out of our comfort zones. 
that morning was a message to me as a photographer to stop being lazy, and shooting what's easy. continue to grow and search for your own places, and perspectives. it's a big world. there's lots to see. alberta is an amazing place, and there's so much of it i still need to see, shoot and explore.

__label__HongKong new blog post: my thoughts on the lack of color in the travel industry #linkinbio

it's a discussion that i get tagged in almost daily in facebook travel groups, so it was long overdue that i put all my thoughts in one place.

blogging is no longer monolithic, and poc influencers exist on every scale of the spectrum.

in a world that tries to paint everything as black and white, there is so much going on in the gray.

the gray of this situation is that iâ€™m doing my best to hustle and grind and make my brand known in a very whitewashed travel industry, regardless of my inherent disadvantage.

but the working twice as hard to get half the recognition gets old quick.

brands, marketers, pr reps, and beyond â€” if youâ€™re continually contracting the same race, religion, gender, and lifestyle brand of bloggers, youâ€™re doing such a disservice to the public.

exercising diversity isnâ€™t something that should be seen as a chore. you should be excited to amplify the voices of minorities, because it will add a different tone, pun intended, [and market, hello $$$] to the mix.

i also tackle the pervasive "put me on" culture, shout out some of the strongest names in the poc blogging space, and give some insight into how we can solve this issue on a larger scale. *5-minute read

anxious to hear your thoughts â¤ bit.ly/lackofcolor #linkinbio

__label__Jaipur,Rajasthan jaipur, famously renowned as the pink city is the royal capital of india's largest state,Â rajasthan. jaipur breathes royalty and wealth. with its gigantic forts, alluring palaces andÂ enormous lifestyle, this city well reminds us of the royal era. if these poised attractions do not tend to mesmerize you, then you could always experience the grandness of it by taking an elephant ride in jaipur. it would definitely be a great experience for you to recall for years. every year hundreds of tourists flock towards the amber fort just for this majestic ride. the beauty of these animals decorated in royal colors would definitely ensorcelled you. these enthralling animals also showcase a great amalgam of painted colours which reflect beautifully. this joy ride takes you to the entrance of theÂ amber fort, up the steep slope. it is definitely a ride worth taking.

the elephant ride up the steep hill commences from the car parking lot and ends at the courtyard of the amber fort. the total duration of the trip is estimated to be around 20 to 30 minutes. the trip duration varies from elephant to elephant and also on the traffic. the cost of taking an elephant ride up this hill is approximately inr 1000 for two. you can enjoy the setting sun while sitting on the back of an elephant.Â this mesmeric view would enthral your senses and would surely give you a taste of royalty to experience. these elephants carry around 900 - 1000 visitors per day, and there are about 80 - 90 elephants in the service. the rajasthan government conducts regular checks to ensure the safety and the welfare of these animals. these checks have been implemented to ensure the safety and limit the cruelty to these animals.

__label__Iceland i have this habit of almost missing flights on the end of a trip. it's seems more often than not the best weather is the day i depart. many all night road trips seem to end with a pack-as-you-drive rush to catch my flight. .
. 
my last trip was thwarted with bad weather all the way until the night before. these rhyolite mountains had been on my list for years to see, so with a few hours of decent weather and clear road conditions we headed out. but if there is one thing you learn in iceland it's to never trust the weather forecast. we took in this view for 30 minutes before freezing rain set in & the entire area was covered in mist. you couldn't see 10 ft in front of you. as if nothing was even there. i've realized that one of best things about traveling is having something worth coming back for. .
@_ryanhill_ @icelandair

__label__Hawaii the king kamehameha statue stands proudly near downtown hilo in the wailoa river state park. it is one of four statues of king kamehameha i. the other three are located in kohala on the big island of hawaii, in downtown honolulu on the island of oahu, and in statuary hall in washington, d.c.

king kamehameha i, also known as kamehameha the great, who was born 1758 or 1737 or 1738 (there is some debate as to the precise year of his birth) and who died in 1819, was one of the most beloved of hawaii's heroes. kamehameha i was the one who conquered the hawaiian islands, unified them and established the kingdom of hawaii in 1810. even during times of intense western influence, his government managed to maintain peace and the traditional values. he developed alliances with the major pacific colonial powers and by doing so preserved hawaii's independence.

__label__Utah i love when a post stirs opinions, like this one. it means people are forced to deal with an ideology or thought process that is different than their own & choose to agree, disagree or educate. i don't ride motorcycles but have a massive respect for that do & understand the need for people to enjoy access to open land for a variety of uses. one of the biggest issues i see is that trying to take a one sided approach to how we use these places alienates many people and interest groups. continuing with this "i'm right, you're wrong" mindset when it comes to public space is what has divided us thus far. although it's a beautiful idea that all nature could be preserved and left in a perfect state ( in a perfect world it would be) it's not the case for us & that also alienates the way some people enjoy land. although this ^ is more disruptive than putting bolts on a wall, taking non native animals outdoors, the romanticized idea of livestock/ farming or creating a mtn bike or hiking trial.. all damage nature in some small way. keep in mind every road we drive on was once unspoiled nature. our homes stand on land that belonged to someone else and may have displaced wildlife. 
for those who have a mind set that this is "just for likes" or some idiotic rhetoric - this place is a long standing and widely used atv and off road area used by thousands and widely enjoyed. photos & videos of it are all over. i share work here i have shot personally and commercially and i can guarantee that my interest in peopleâ€™s â€˜likesâ€™ is the least motivating force behind what i shoot and share. i would implore you to think before speaking, commenting and try to understand the motivation behind such a post. if people did the smallest bit of research they would understand that my greatest goal is to challenge how people think and view roles in the environment. doing that doesnâ€™t always mean you embrace popular opinion.â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€” .

__label__PlanetEarth over the years the idea of living self sustained has become more & more important to me. or maybe i'm just wanting to rely less on things i personally can't control. we run our office off solar, house from a well pump & leach field, raise chickens & ducks and in the past have grown many to most of our own veggies. what we can't make ourselves we try to borrow from friends & neighbors. none of it is easy.. ever & it won't begging to offset the carbon footprint - but its a start. 
its a process to constantly look for ways we can be less dependent on others for power, food & waste. it will never be flawless & its always been an investment, but its one worth making for a brighter future.
.

this dome & other dwellings have always been a beautiful representation to me of impermanent structures leaving little to no trace.

__label__Zanzibar,Tanzania ask me anything ğŸ¤”
q3 by @jenygoesplaces - "years down this journey, what do you feel about the life you left? do you see yourself going back to a job and settling down at a place?"
.
.
i sometimes think of my two years of corporate life, the 9 to 5 routine, working with a great team on social media strategies, of the money that landed up in my account every month without fail... and i compare it to my current life, that gives me the freedom to pick up my bags and leave for where my heart longs, to stay as long as i want in far off corners of the world, to have created a living out of something i love (writing and social media), of the money that sometimes shows up and sometimes doesn't. both lifestyles have their pros and cons, but i know the latter is for me, i choose freedom and adventure over  stability and money.
.
.
to everyone who asks me what i'm chasing with all this travel, i want to ask what we are chasing in a "regular" life? if we are chasing a (false) sense of security through a steady job and a legal relationship and a house we own, then that's exactly what i aspire to run from. from the illusion that i control my life and the future. .
.
the road is like a mirror for my personal life. you know all those friendships and relationships we bank on? when you're always away, you learn which of your relationships are real enough to survive time and distance. so i might have much fewer "real" relationships now - some from my earlier life, some from the road - but they feel so much more real to me than a room full of pseudo friends. .
.
i don't see myself working 9 to 5 again, or for someone else. but i do dream of a place where i can maybe spend 6 months every year, surrounded by nature, grow my own produce and start a sustainable travel initiative... so far, it's just a distant dream ğŸ˜‡
.
.
and you, what does your journey in life currently look like? what are you chasing?
.
.

__label__Barcelona,Spain today the unthinkable happened in barcelona happened - it rained! lol it actually wasn't bad for what i wanted to see and do and it even added a nice moody touch to a planned lunch along the beach with my other @aktravel_usa participants. funny thing about barcelona's long sandy shorefront; it didn't exist before the 1992 olympic games. those games were actually a turning point for the city, forcing it into long overdo improvements including moving the massive industries once located along the water and turning it into the sunny beachside residents never thought they'd see. so that's why, sun or not, spending time along barcelona's beaches isn't just fun, it's a big part of the overall city experience. #aktravel

__label__Lima,Peru hey y'all! just your friendly reminder this valentine's day -- that being single doesn't suck, it's your mentality that does.

the happiness you're trying to find in someone else should be rooted internally first.

if you're looking for someone to complete you, you've bought into the flawed ideology that you're inadequate on your own.

you will never find happiness in someone else if you can't learn to be happy on your own first.

so treat yourself to your favorite meal.
binge-watch your favorite show.
and most importantly, fall asleep diagonally.

oh, and pro tip for the men: if your lady says you don't have to get her anything on valentine's day, it is the biggest trap of all time and i hope you didn't fall for it.
